Anyway, so it shows
a cell over here

00:03:46.380 --> 00:03:48.822
captured with a microscope--

00:03:48.822 --> 00:03:50.655
which, I believe, is a
confocal microscopes.

00:03:50.655 --> 00:03:53.590
So it is Professor
Sheppard's expertise.

00:03:53.590 --> 00:03:57.990
And this is the picture of the
esophagus of a person captured

00:03:57.990 --> 00:03:58.900
with an endoscopy.

00:03:58.900 --> 00:04:03.660
So they basically lower
the fiber bundle inside,

00:04:03.660 --> 00:04:06.120
down someone's throat.

00:04:06.120 --> 00:04:09.060
And using a technique called
optical coherence tomography--

00:04:09.060 --> 00:04:11.310
it is an optical
imaging technique--

00:04:11.310 --> 00:04:15.020
they capture the esophagus.

00:04:15.020 --> 00:04:18.329
And so finally,
what you see here

00:04:18.329 --> 00:04:20.250
is, of course, an optical
disk, if you're not

00:04:20.250 --> 00:04:21.510
familiar with those.

00:04:21.510 --> 00:04:24.530
And over here I believe
that's a holographic setup.

00:04:24.530 --> 00:04:27.360
It is a diffusion
screen, and this

00:04:27.360 --> 00:04:32.010
is supposed to be a setup for
a three-dimensional display.

00:04:32.010 --> 00:04:34.320
When you look at it,
it creates the illusion

00:04:34.320 --> 00:04:37.410
