00:04:58.740 --> 00:05:01.710
Samsung offers a 3D TV set.

00:05:01.710 --> 00:05:05.370
Anyway, so the
point of this slide

00:05:05.370 --> 00:05:09.240
is that there's many
applications of optics that

00:05:09.240 --> 00:05:11.430
are interesting in engineering.

00:05:11.430 --> 00:05:14.520
And, of course,
light phenomena are

00:05:14.520 --> 00:05:16.630
interesting in their own right.

00:05:16.630 --> 00:05:22.475
So the class will try to
balance curiosity-based,

00:05:22.475 --> 00:05:23.850
more of a science
approach, where

00:05:23.850 --> 00:05:27.060
we learn basic facts
about how light behaves,

00:05:27.060 --> 00:05:29.790
how it propagates, how
it interacts with matter,

00:05:29.790 --> 00:05:32.270
and we'll balance those with
engineering applications that

00:05:32.270 --> 00:05:36.760
are, presumably, of
interest to many of you.

00:05:36.760 --> 00:05:39.730
And for issues that have to
do with the expertise of both

00:05:39.730 --> 00:05:43.090
of us, both of the
instructors, we

00:05:43.090 --> 00:05:46.400
will concentrate most of
the applications on imaging.

00:05:46.400 --> 00:05:49.150
So we'll be dealing a lot
with things like microscopes

00:05:49.150 --> 00:05:51.260
and telescopes primarily.

00:05:51.260 --> 00:05:56.500
These the major
imaging instruments.

00:05:56.500 --> 00:05:58.630
But we'll also cover some
other things for fun.

00:05:58.630 --> 00:06:01.060
For example, we'll talk
about the human eye.

00:06:01.060 --> 00:06:05.510
We'll describe its structure,
its biology, how it works--

00:06:05.510 --> 00:06:07.510
not in great detail,
because this is, after all,

00:06:07.510 --> 00:06:09.220
not a biology class.

00:06:09.220 --> 00:06:11.590
But just for fun,
because of the human eye

00:06:11.590 --> 00:06:15.130
turns out to have some very
interesting optics inside it.

00:06:15.130 --> 00:06:17.380
And also, we'll
discuss very briefly

00:06:17.380 --> 00:06:20.830
the eyes of insects, which, as
you can see from the picture

00:06:20.830 --> 00:06:23.740
and you may already
know, they're very

00:06:23.740 --> 00:06:25.870
different than the human eye.

00:06:25.870 --> 00:06:28.820
And we'll discuss a little
bit why they're different

00:06:28.820 --> 00:06:31.490
and how each one
of them operates.

00:06:31.490 --> 00:06:33.970
And finally, some other
optical imaging systems that

00:06:33.970 --> 00:06:35.770
look very surprising.

00:06:35.770 --> 00:06:38.770
This picture over
here is an instrument

00:06:38.770 --> 00:06:41.920
called the Very Large
Array telescope, or VLA.

00:06:41.920 --> 00:06:46.410
It is located in Socorro, New
Mexico, here in the States.

00:06:46.410 --> 00:06:50.470
And it is composed
of 27 antennas.

00:06:50.470 --> 00:06:53.350
Each one of these little
white things is an antenna.

00:06:53.350 --> 00:06:58.280
It's about 27 meters tall, and
the diameter of the instrument,

00:06:58.280 --> 00:07:01.930
this branch over here,
is approximately--

00:07:01.930 --> 00:07:02.740
well, it varies.

00:07:02.740 --> 00:07:05.080
I don't know what it was
when this picture was taken.

00:07:05.080 --> 00:07:07.520
But it can between 3 miles--

00:07:07.520 --> 00:07:11.080
the diameter that is the size
of Cambridge, Massachusetts--

00:07:11.080 --> 00:07:15.040
and 15 miles-- that is the
size of Washington, DC.

00:07:15.040 --> 00:07:16.210
So that is an instrument.

00:07:16.210 --> 00:07:18.085
An optical instrument,
if you can believe it,

00:07:18.085 --> 00:07:21.580
has the size of an
entire state in the US.

00:07:21.580 --> 00:07:25.450
And it is used to observe
very remote galaxies

00:07:25.450 --> 00:07:27.310
with high resolution.

00:07:27.310 --> 00:07:29.650
So it falls a little bit
outside the scope of the class,

00:07:29.650 --> 00:07:34.690
because it uses it uses
statistical optics, which

00:07:34.690 --> 00:07:37.390
we don't cover over here,
but we may mention it

00:07:37.390 --> 00:07:40.720
in passing a little bit later.

00:07:40.720 --> 00:07:44.320
So this is, of course,
among other things

00:07:44.320 --> 00:07:46.780
