00:18:44.120 --> 00:18:47.000
light interacts with matter,
and how it propagates, and so.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:49.640
It is really a
horrendous problem.

00:18:49.640 --> 00:18:51.950
But over the years--
over the centuries,

00:18:51.950 --> 00:18:55.030
actually-- people have come up
with different approximations

00:18:55.030 --> 00:18:56.800
of progressive accuracy.

00:18:56.800 --> 00:18:59.330
So geometrical optics is
the simplest approximation

00:18:59.330 --> 00:19:03.170
that gives you very simple
formulas, very simple math,

00:19:03.170 --> 00:19:07.280
and actually describes light
quite well up to a point.

00:19:07.280 --> 00:19:09.710
So we'll do that
first, and then we'll

00:19:09.710 --> 00:19:13.160
graduate to wave optics,
which is a little bit more

00:19:13.160 --> 00:19:15.800
involved mathematically,
but it also

00:19:15.800 --> 00:19:21.380
gives better approximations
about the propagation of light.

00:19:21.380 --> 00:19:24.750
And then, finally, in
the very last few--

00:19:24.750 --> 00:19:27.590
probably in the last lecture,
and only if we have time--

00:19:27.590 --> 00:19:31.070
we'll cover a topic called
sub-wavelength optics, which is

00:19:31.070 --> 00:19:32.510
an even better approximation.

00:19:32.510 --> 00:19:37.790
But that is actually pretty much
impossible to do analytically.

00:19:37.790 --> 00:19:39.890
So one has to go onto
a computer and do

00:19:39.890 --> 00:19:44.090
