00:20:26.810 --> 00:20:29.798
Let me start with a
little bit of history.

00:20:29.798 --> 00:20:31.840
This, of course, is not
the subject of the class,

00:20:31.840 --> 00:20:33.790
but it's kind of fun to do.

00:20:33.790 --> 00:20:37.320
I used to start my classes with
a joke that not everybody got.

00:20:37.320 --> 00:20:40.090
I used to start by
saying that optics

00:20:40.090 --> 00:20:41.800
is the most ancient science.

00:20:41.800 --> 00:20:43.240
Not the most
ancient profession--

00:20:43.240 --> 00:20:44.480
that's something else--

00:20:44.480 --> 00:20:45.820
but is the most ancient science.

00:20:48.830 --> 00:20:52.420
And I think the reason
is because humans

00:20:52.420 --> 00:20:55.330
are very visual animals.

00:20:55.330 --> 00:21:00.160
Our vision, for those of us who
are lucky enough to have it,

00:21:00.160 --> 00:21:03.460
our vision is one of them
most dominant census.

00:21:03.460 --> 00:21:07.240
So people got interested in
phenomena involving light

00:21:07.240 --> 00:21:11.440
relatively early on
in the early ages.

00:21:11.440 --> 00:21:13.870
And this probably happened
across civilizations--

00:21:13.870 --> 00:21:19.340
Chinese, Egyptian,
Western Greek, and so on.

00:21:19.340 --> 00:21:22.960
But as it happens, the Greeks
were the only ones to publish.

00:21:22.960 --> 00:21:25.510
They were open about what
they were discovering.

00:21:25.510 --> 00:21:28.060
The Egyptians and the
Chinese, the priests

00:21:28.060 --> 00:21:30.690
kept everything under control.

00:21:30.690 --> 00:21:32.440
So we don't know much
about what they did.

00:21:32.440 --> 00:21:35.560
But from what we've
discovered, archaeologists

00:21:35.560 --> 00:21:38.710
have discovered in ancient
tombs and so on, they also

00:21:38.710 --> 00:21:39.940
knew quite a bit about light.

00:21:43.630 --> 00:21:46.300
Of course, the Greeks
made the major mistake--

00:21:46.300 --> 00:21:49.570
so Greek science
was very interesting

00:21:49.570 --> 00:21:52.730
because it was the flip
side of modern science.

00:21:52.730 --> 00:22:01.570
The Greeks had the attitude
that you can understand nature

00:22:01.570 --> 00:22:03.970
just by thinking.

00:22:03.970 --> 00:22:07.950
So the Greeks actually
discouraged experiment.

00:22:07.950 --> 00:22:12.450
Strangely enough, this tradition
has followed the Greek psyche,

00:22:12.450 --> 00:22:13.950
because if you
look at the faculty

00:22:13.950 --> 00:22:16.110
in the mechanical
engineering department,

00:22:16.110 --> 00:22:21.030
there's a lot of Greeks, or
professors of Greek origin,

00:22:21.030 --> 00:22:22.870
and lots of them
are theoreticians.

00:22:22.870 --> 00:22:25.590
Anyway, I'm just joking.

00:22:25.590 --> 00:22:27.480
But anyway, the
ancient Greeks, they

00:22:27.480 --> 00:22:30.110
have this attitude that you
don't need to do experiment.

00:22:30.110 --> 00:22:32.070
In fact, you must
not do experiment.

00:22:32.070 --> 00:22:36.790
You have to understand
everything by thought.

00:22:36.790 --> 00:22:39.383
So because of that, they came
up with some strange ideas.

00:22:39.383 --> 00:22:41.050
So for example, the
Greeks, they thought

00:22:41.050 --> 00:22:46.210
that when you look at something,
your eyes emit some substance,

00:22:46.210 --> 00:22:49.090
which they called simulacra.

00:22:49.090 --> 00:22:54.940
And this absence is their
thought of what light is.

00:22:54.940 --> 00:22:57.610
So I look at you, I
transmit a substance.

00:22:57.610 --> 00:23:00.610
The substance comes back to
me, and that's how I see you.

00:23:00.610 --> 00:23:02.930
Which is, of course, a
very bizarre, bizarre way

00:23:02.930 --> 00:23:03.430
of thinking.

00:23:03.430 --> 00:23:05.500
But anyway, that's
what they thought.

00:23:05.500 --> 00:23:11.050
And it was the Arabs, much
later in the 10th century or so,

00:23:11.050 --> 00:23:13.917
who read the Greek script.

00:23:13.917 --> 00:23:16.250
And they said, well, that
doesn't make any sense at all.

00:23:16.250 --> 00:23:17.625
So the Arabs, for
the first time,

00:23:17.625 --> 00:23:19.840
thought, well, it must
be the other way around.

00:23:19.840 --> 00:23:23.620
There must be light sources,
like the sun, or a fire, or--

00:23:23.620 --> 00:23:24.900
that's about it at the time.

00:23:24.900 --> 00:23:28.090
They didn't have
light bulbs yet.

00:23:28.090 --> 00:23:32.590
So it must be that they emit
something that is called light,

00:23:32.590 --> 00:23:34.156
and that's how we see.

00:23:34.156 --> 00:23:36.920
So it took us about
1,000 years, I guess,

00:23:36.920 --> 00:23:40.520
to resolve that question.

00:23:40.520 --> 00:23:44.100
And also, the Arabs did a lot
of the very first basic work

00:23:44.100 --> 00:23:44.600
in optics.

00:23:44.600 --> 00:23:47.810
For example, Snell's Law,
the law of refraction

00:23:47.810 --> 00:23:50.030
that I will cover
in a little bit,

00:23:50.030 --> 00:23:53.740
the Arabs discovered it first.

00:23:53.740 --> 00:23:59.470
And then, much later,
another 400 years later,

00:23:59.470 --> 00:24:03.010
Descartes, he did two things.

00:24:03.010 --> 00:24:06.110
He put the basic
foundations of science--

00:24:06.110 --> 00:24:11.300
Descartes, you may
know this, Descartes

00:24:11.300 --> 00:24:14.000
was the first
philosopher, I should say,

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:16.890
who flipped the
Greek point of view.

00:24:16.890 --> 00:24:19.160
And he said that it's
actually the other way around.

00:24:19.160 --> 00:24:22.070
Science must follow experiment.

00:24:22.070 --> 00:24:24.800
Instead of just thinking about
nature and explaining it,

00:24:24.800 --> 00:24:26.570
he said that it's the
other way around--

00:24:26.570 --> 00:24:29.000
science must be
driven by observation.

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:32.060
So we observe something, we
create experimental conditions

00:24:32.060 --> 00:24:36.080
to test it, and then we
come up with a theory

00:24:36.080 --> 00:24:39.050
that tries to explain the
observation-- not the other way

00:24:39.050 --> 00:24:39.750
around.

00:24:39.750 --> 00:24:46.067
And of course, modern science
still follows that principle.

00:24:46.067 --> 00:24:47.150
At least hopefully, right?

00:24:47.150 --> 00:24:49.910
Because there have
been occasions

00:24:49.910 --> 00:24:51.560
of cheating and so on.

00:24:51.560 --> 00:24:54.170
You probably see
those in newspapers.

00:24:54.170 --> 00:24:56.060
I think there was
a guy who invented,

00:24:56.060 --> 00:24:58.930
who sort of created
data at HP Labs.

00:24:58.930 --> 00:25:01.180
Was it HP Labs?

00:25:01.180 --> 00:25:03.730
Anyway, so there are some
people who violated principle.

00:25:03.730 --> 00:25:07.500
But hopefully, 99.9999%
of us will actually

00:25:07.500 --> 00:25:08.500
follow Descartes, right?

00:25:08.500 --> 00:25:12.820
We make an observation,
we report it faithfully,

00:25:12.820 --> 00:25:15.440
and then we try to explain
it to the best we can

00:25:15.440 --> 00:25:17.020
and in the simplest
way that we can.

00:25:17.020 --> 00:25:21.290
That's the scientific method.

00:25:21.290 --> 00:25:23.650
But also, Descartes, as it
turns out, worked on optics.

00:25:23.650 --> 00:25:27.370
And he also derived
Snell's Law in his own way.

00:25:27.370 --> 00:25:30.550
And there's something called
the Descartes Sphere, which

00:25:30.550 --> 00:25:32.650
was invented
independently by the Arabs

00:25:32.650 --> 00:25:35.260
in the 11th century
or 12th, I forget--

00:25:35.260 --> 00:25:41.050
Ninth, actually--
and then Descartes

00:25:41.050 --> 00:25:46.710
reinvented it about
400 or 500 years later.

00:25:46.710 --> 00:25:49.635
Then, the next major advance
in optics came from Newton--

00:25:52.530 --> 00:25:54.720
actually, Newton and
Huygens, who tried to explain

00:25:54.720 --> 00:25:56.790
light in two different ways.

00:25:56.790 --> 00:25:58.650
Newton was of the
opinion that light

00:25:58.650 --> 00:26:02.970
is a bunch of particles
that travel in air.

00:26:02.970 --> 00:26:07.890
And he tried to explain various
phenomena like refraction

00:26:07.890 --> 00:26:11.790
from a prism, and so
on, based on this idea.

00:26:11.790 --> 00:26:13.830
Huygens thought that
light is a wave very

00:26:13.830 --> 00:26:15.380
similar to water waves.

00:26:15.380 --> 00:26:16.690
They did not know about--

00:26:16.690 --> 00:26:21.042
I believe Newton also
postulated that sound is a wave.

00:26:21.042 --> 00:26:22.500
But for some reason,
Newton thought

00:26:22.500 --> 00:26:24.550
that light is not a wave.

00:26:24.550 --> 00:26:25.950
In fact, the two of them fought.

00:26:25.950 --> 00:26:30.780
I don't know if the fought over
it, but they disagreed over it.

00:26:30.780 --> 00:26:33.960
But I guess because
Newton was more famous--

00:26:33.960 --> 00:26:39.090
he was a professor, a Lucasian
professor at Cambridge--

00:26:39.090 --> 00:26:43.060
so Newton's view
actually prevailed

00:26:43.060 --> 00:26:46.470
for several years, prevailed.

00:26:46.470 --> 00:26:49.080
And the particle
theory of light was

00:26:49.080 --> 00:26:52.590
dominant until about
a century later

00:26:52.590 --> 00:26:55.410
when people experimentally--

00:26:55.410 --> 00:26:57.540
again, here comes the
scientific method--

00:26:57.540 --> 00:27:01.620
people experimentally observed
phenomena like interference

00:27:01.620 --> 00:27:06.900
that would only be described
if light were a wave.

00:27:06.900 --> 00:27:09.240
So the particle theory
got a big hit then,

00:27:09.240 --> 00:27:13.290
because it could not explain
diffraction, interference,

00:27:13.290 --> 00:27:14.370
and so on, and so forth.

00:27:14.370 --> 00:27:17.760
But yet, people were observing
them in the laboratory.

00:27:17.760 --> 00:27:20.620
Of course, now, after
one more century, people

00:27:20.620 --> 00:27:22.230
discovered that, guess what?

00:27:22.230 --> 00:27:23.790
Both theories are correct.

00:27:23.790 --> 00:27:26.520
With quantum mechanics,
light can be thought of as

00:27:26.520 --> 00:27:29.490
both as particle and as a wave.

00:27:29.490 --> 00:27:32.640
And in fact, Einstein and
some other scientists--

00:27:32.640 --> 00:27:34.480
Schrodinger, Planck, and so on--

00:27:34.480 --> 00:27:39.520
they reconciled the
two points of view.

00:27:39.520 --> 00:27:41.940
Not perfectly-- there
still some puzzling aspects

00:27:41.940 --> 00:27:44.770
of the quantum theory of light.

00:27:44.770 --> 00:27:46.330
But I think
nowadays, most people

00:27:46.330 --> 00:27:48.010
are comfortable with
the idea that you

00:27:48.010 --> 00:27:51.940
can use both approaches to
describe light phenomena.

00:27:51.940 --> 00:27:54.340
You simply select
the ones that best

00:27:54.340 --> 00:27:57.670
suits your approximations
and your conditions

00:27:57.670 --> 00:27:58.970
at any given moment.

00:27:58.970 --> 00:28:01.420
So for example, if
a particle approach

00:28:01.420 --> 00:28:04.730
is sufficient to describe the
phenomenon, then you use it.

00:28:04.730 --> 00:28:07.570
And of course, there's also,
typically-- or, not typically,

00:28:07.570 --> 00:28:09.730
always--

00:28:09.730 --> 00:28:10.660
let me restate.

00:28:10.660 --> 00:28:15.100
There had better be an
equivalent wave description

00:28:15.100 --> 00:28:17.620
of whatever phenomenon
you're describing,

00:28:17.620 --> 00:28:19.320
but it may be more
complicated, right?

00:28:19.320 --> 00:28:21.980
So in that case, you
use particle theory.

00:28:21.980 --> 00:28:22.980
Or the other way around.

00:28:22.980 --> 00:28:26.410
If it is easier to describe
something as a wave,

00:28:26.410 --> 00:28:30.513
you opt for the
wave description.

00:28:30.513 --> 00:28:32.930
So of course, in this class,
we don't cover quantum optics

00:28:32.930 --> 00:28:33.430
at all.

00:28:33.430 --> 00:28:36.050
Professor Shapiro in the
electrical engineering

00:28:36.050 --> 00:28:39.110
department offers a
class in quantum optics.

00:28:39.110 --> 00:28:41.630
And I suppose that there
is also a quantum optics

00:28:41.630 --> 00:28:45.080
glass for those of you
who are interested.

00:28:45.080 --> 00:28:46.250
It's a very elegant topic.

00:28:49.050 --> 00:28:54.260
So the other major
advance in optics

00:28:54.260 --> 00:28:58.700
came in the middle
of the last century,

00:28:58.700 --> 00:29:04.160
when the laser was
invented and the technique

00:29:04.160 --> 00:29:07.780
called holography called
holographic was invented.

00:29:07.780 --> 00:29:11.420
Not because holography is
somehow dominant in practice.

00:29:11.420 --> 00:29:14.345
I mean, you see holograms
typically in museums.

00:29:14.345 --> 00:29:15.640
It's no big deal.

00:29:15.640 --> 00:29:18.530
But holography turned out
to be a very interesting

00:29:18.530 --> 00:29:21.800
mathematical way of
looking at optics.

00:29:21.800 --> 00:29:23.510
Now, that really
had a major impact

00:29:23.510 --> 00:29:28.520
in the subsequent development
of optical science.

00:29:28.520 --> 00:29:30.800
So for this reason,
both of these inventions

00:29:30.800 --> 00:29:33.260
led to Nobel prizes.

00:29:33.260 --> 00:29:37.320
They were very major advances
in the field of light.

00:29:37.320 --> 00:29:43.150
And especially after the
invention of the laser,

00:29:43.150 --> 00:29:45.460
optical science
had a huge impact

00:29:45.460 --> 00:29:46.630
on everyday applications.

00:29:46.630 --> 00:29:48.070
If you think about
devices you use

00:29:48.070 --> 00:29:52.750
in your everyday life, every
time you pick up a telephone

00:29:52.750 --> 00:29:56.262
or you use the internet,
there's typically-- especially

00:29:56.262 --> 00:29:58.720
if you use it long-distance--
there's some optics involved.

00:29:58.720 --> 00:30:03.040
Because the signals propagate
through optical fibers,

00:30:03.040 --> 00:30:08.530
at least in part of the
telecommunications network.

00:30:08.530 --> 00:30:10.950
If you're unlucky
enough to have surgery,

00:30:10.950 --> 00:30:14.560
there's many kinds
of laser surgery.

00:30:14.560 --> 00:30:17.470
Lots of clinical
medical diagnosis

00:30:17.470 --> 00:30:19.840
is done using
high-end microscopes,

00:30:19.840 --> 00:30:22.840
including confocal microscopes,
optical coherence tomographers,

00:30:22.840 --> 00:30:23.920
and so on, and so forth.

00:30:23.920 --> 00:30:26.700
These are all
commercial instruments.

00:30:26.700 --> 00:30:28.620
There's applications
in industry--

00:30:28.620 --> 00:30:32.820
for example, laser cutting,
laser welding, laser metrology

00:30:32.820 --> 00:30:39.990
that is used in high-end
precision engineering

00:30:39.990 --> 00:30:41.010
applications.

00:30:41.010 --> 00:30:44.040
And of course, finally, every
time you pick up a computer,

00:30:44.040 --> 00:30:47.520
the chips that are all made
using optical lithography,

00:30:47.520 --> 00:30:52.590
which is a really highly
sophisticated form of optical

00:30:52.590 --> 00:30:53.580
imagine.

00:30:53.580 --> 00:30:57.000
And I use the term "optical"
here in a very general way.

00:30:57.000 --> 00:30:58.440
Most of it is really optical.

00:30:58.440 --> 00:30:59.670
We use light.

00:30:59.670 --> 00:31:02.430
In some really extreme,
high-end applications,

00:31:02.430 --> 00:31:04.290
they use electron lithography.

00:31:04.290 --> 00:31:08.940
But still electrons, behave like
light when it comes to this,

00:31:08.940 --> 00:31:10.500
to this scale.

00:31:10.500 --> 00:31:14.740
So basically, the same equations
that we use to describe light,

00:31:14.740 --> 00:31:19.050
they use them to describe
imaging by electrons.

00:31:19.050 --> 00:31:26.930
So that is really a huge, huge,
huge domain of application.

00:31:26.930 --> 00:31:30.450
It still remains a very
active scientific field.

00:31:30.450 --> 00:31:32.340
So if you look at the
list of Nobel Prizes--

00:31:32.340 --> 00:31:36.080
this is a very incomplete list
that I compiled from the Nobel

00:31:36.080 --> 00:31:37.970
website--

00:31:37.970 --> 00:31:42.320
even that latest Nobel
Prize that was awarded--

00:31:42.320 --> 00:31:45.740
in chemistry, actually; it
was in the field of optics--

00:31:45.740 --> 00:31:49.010
these fellows, they
invented something,

00:31:49.010 --> 00:31:53.675
green fluorescent
protein, which is--

00:31:53.675 --> 00:31:55.880
I may embarrass myself
now, because I don't

00:31:55.880 --> 00:31:57.200
understand the biology of it,

00:31:57.200 --> 00:32:00.020
But my very simple
understanding is

00:32:00.020 --> 00:32:03.920
that they can genetically
program this protein

00:32:03.920 --> 00:32:07.020
to get into some animals' DNA.

00:32:07.020 --> 00:32:10.430
So they basically create animals
that have this protein embedded

00:32:10.430 --> 00:32:13.340
in their genes, and
then these proteins

00:32:13.340 --> 00:32:18.655
can also be designed to turn
itself on or off depending

00:32:18.655 --> 00:32:19.780
on happens with the animal.

00:32:19.780 --> 00:32:22.610
For example, if the animal
is exposed to a disease,

00:32:22.610 --> 00:32:25.550
or if it is exposed to a
certain chemical agent,

00:32:25.550 --> 00:32:28.100
or anyway, whatever
is of interest

00:32:28.100 --> 00:32:31.790
to the particular
biological experiment,

00:32:31.790 --> 00:32:35.330
it sounds kind of funny, but
the animal becomes fluorescent.

00:32:35.330 --> 00:32:38.330
Or more interestingly,
certain parts

00:32:38.330 --> 00:32:40.110
of the tissue of the
animal-- for example,

00:32:40.110 --> 00:32:44.510
the liver, or some tissue of
interest-- becomes fluorescent.

00:32:44.510 --> 00:32:48.230
So then you can pump the
animal with a laser beam,

00:32:48.230 --> 00:32:50.660
you can measure the
fluorescence that is coming out

00:32:50.660 --> 00:32:52.670
of the animal's
tissue, and then you

00:32:52.670 --> 00:32:55.940
can derive conclusions about
what happened to the animal.

00:32:55.940 --> 00:33:00.830
So this is a fantastic way of
studying genetics, studying

00:33:00.830 --> 00:33:05.960
diseases, studying a number of
different and very important

00:33:05.960 --> 00:33:07.400
biological phenomena.

00:33:07.400 --> 00:33:08.780
So for that reason,
these fellows

00:33:08.780 --> 00:33:11.810
were awarded the Nobel Prize.

00:33:11.810 --> 00:33:14.600
And actually, many
people, including myself--

00:33:14.600 --> 00:33:19.210
at least not yet, but I'm
sure in Colin's lab, already,

00:33:19.210 --> 00:33:24.860
we'll use animals
that are genetically

00:33:24.860 --> 00:33:25.940
modified with this--

00:33:25.940 --> 00:33:28.700
It's called GFC, green
fluorescent protein--

00:33:28.700 --> 00:33:30.980
to study various
biological phenomena.

00:33:30.980 --> 00:33:34.550
Now it is a very commonly
used technique in microscopy.

00:33:34.550 --> 00:33:38.780
So this was the most recent
optics-related Nobel Prize.

00:33:38.780 --> 00:33:41.810
There's a bunch of others.

00:33:41.810 --> 00:33:43.825
My favorite is actually--

00:33:43.825 --> 00:33:44.900
where is it?

00:33:44.900 --> 00:33:46.430
This one.

00:33:46.430 --> 00:33:51.010
In 1997, this was a
given for optical traps.

00:33:51.010 --> 00:33:52.640
So an optical trap
is actually a way

00:33:52.640 --> 00:33:54.860
to move particles
by using light.

00:33:54.860 --> 00:33:58.370
It's a very surprising
thing, because none

00:33:58.370 --> 00:34:02.210
of us in everyday life will
experience mechanical force

00:34:02.210 --> 00:34:03.680
from a light beam.

00:34:03.680 --> 00:34:05.027
But in actuality, there is one.

00:34:05.027 --> 00:34:06.860
If you are sitting in
the back of the light,

00:34:06.860 --> 00:34:08.090
you are feeling the force.

00:34:08.090 --> 00:34:09.100
This once is very weak.

00:34:09.100 --> 00:34:11.370
It's in the range of
femtonewtons, typically--

00:34:11.370 --> 00:34:14.550
a really tiny, tiny force.

00:34:14.550 --> 00:34:18.020
But we're also very big, so the
force is not enough to move us.

00:34:18.020 --> 00:34:20.300
But if you're really tiny--
like a cell, for example--

00:34:20.300 --> 00:34:22.730
the force, especially if
you design the optical right

00:34:22.730 --> 00:34:24.860
with a very highly
focused beam, you

00:34:24.860 --> 00:34:26.860
can boost that
force to the range

00:34:26.860 --> 00:34:28.770
of, perhaps, a few piconewtons.

00:34:28.770 --> 00:34:31.010
Not really that's a very
high force, but anyway,

00:34:31.010 --> 00:34:32.989
in that order of
magnitude, it can

00:34:32.989 --> 00:34:35.690
be enough to actually
move a particle.

00:34:35.690 --> 00:34:41.520
So you can make, you can apply
mechanical forces using light.

00:34:41.520 --> 00:34:44.719
So this was another Nobel Prize.

00:34:44.719 --> 00:34:48.110
So anyway, the reason
I'm bringing this up

00:34:48.110 --> 00:34:50.270
is because this is a
very exciting field.

00:34:50.270 --> 00:34:52.469
At least-- well, I'm partial,
because I work on it,

00:34:52.469 --> 00:34:54.380
but it's a very exciting field.

00:34:54.380 --> 00:34:58.970
People come up with clever,
crazy inventions all the time.

00:34:58.970 --> 00:35:02.810
And many, many of
these inventions have--

00:35:02.810 --> 00:35:05.570
usually, they have
a very high impact.

00:35:05.570 --> 00:35:11.450
And so it is interesting to
see both sides of the coin,

00:35:11.450 --> 00:35:13.730
both the science
side of the coin

00:35:13.730 --> 00:35:16.820
that is purely
curiosity-driven, and very often

00:35:16.820 --> 00:35:19.190
people in government
question it,

00:35:19.190 --> 00:35:21.410
because they say, well,
why are you guys doing

00:35:21.410 --> 00:35:22.940
all this crazy stuff?

00:35:22.940 --> 00:35:25.100
Who cares about optical forces?

00:35:25.100 --> 00:35:26.900
But of course, these
people are so excited,

00:35:26.900 --> 00:35:31.310
because history shows
that most of the time,

00:35:31.310 --> 00:35:33.650
these curiosity-driven
discoveries,

00:35:33.650 --> 00:35:37.040
they end up having a huge
impact in everyday life.

00:35:37.040 --> 00:35:44.540
Some crazy persons-- they
were French, American,

00:35:44.540 --> 00:35:46.010
and Chinese-American, right?

00:35:46.010 --> 00:35:48.680
Three crazy persons
thought about focusing

00:35:48.680 --> 00:35:50.180
light to move particles.

00:35:50.180 --> 00:35:53.030
Then, all of a sudden, this
is used in biological research

00:35:53.030 --> 00:35:55.940
to try to understand
diseases like malaria.

00:35:55.940 --> 00:35:58.470
I don't know if any of Professor
Subra Suresh's students

00:35:58.470 --> 00:36:03.410
are here, but one of my
colleagues, Subra Suresh,

00:36:03.410 --> 00:36:05.840
studied malaria using
this technique that

00:36:05.840 --> 00:36:09.530
won the Nobel Prize in 1997.

00:36:09.530 --> 00:36:13.350
So it is our duty as
engineers, or scientists,

00:36:13.350 --> 00:36:15.650
or whatever the case
may be to emphasize

00:36:15.650 --> 00:36:17.750
to the people in
government and politics

00:36:17.750 --> 00:36:21.450
that yes, there is value
in fundamental science

00:36:21.450 --> 00:36:23.550
when they bash it
and they say that,

00:36:23.550 --> 00:36:27.820
what, you guys are playing
in laboratories, and so on.

00:36:27.820 --> 00:36:30.380
OK, so I went onto my tirade.

00:36:30.380 --> 00:36:34.288
And any questions?

00:36:38.212 --> 00:36:39.170
AUDIENCE: I've got one.

00:36:39.170 --> 00:36:40.212
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Yes.

00:36:40.212 --> 00:36:42.200
AUDIENCE: So I think I'm on.

00:36:42.200 --> 00:36:45.015
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Yes, can you hear him?

00:36:45.015 --> 00:36:45.560
OK.

00:36:45.560 --> 00:36:47.185
AUDIENCE: It says
that you can describe

00:36:47.185 --> 00:36:50.640
how an electron beam images
in a similar way as optics.

00:36:50.640 --> 00:36:52.500
But electrons
interact with matter.

00:36:52.500 --> 00:36:54.428
So how does light
interact with matter?

00:36:54.428 --> 00:36:55.470
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Yes.

00:36:55.470 --> 00:36:56.490
So we will cover that.

00:36:56.490 --> 00:36:59.880
Of course, they interact in
very different ways, right?

00:36:59.880 --> 00:37:03.920
The fundamental difference is
that electrons are fermions,

00:37:03.920 --> 00:37:09.400
so they cannot really
be in the same state.

00:37:09.400 --> 00:37:15.090
Photons are bosons, so they can
actually be in the same state.

00:37:15.090 --> 00:37:17.360
So what I really should
have said-- and thank you

00:37:17.360 --> 00:37:20.600
for pointing it out--
is that in free space,

00:37:20.600 --> 00:37:22.340
they're described by
the same equations.

00:37:22.340 --> 00:37:24.380
Of course, when they
get inside matter,

00:37:24.380 --> 00:37:27.062
their behavior is
quite different.

00:37:27.062 --> 00:37:28.520
But again, for
example, if you look

00:37:28.520 --> 00:37:31.220
at the electrons that go
ballistically through matter,

00:37:31.220 --> 00:37:34.880
they experience an effect that
is very similar to refraction.

00:37:34.880 --> 00:37:36.350
So you can describe--

00:37:36.350 --> 00:37:38.550
you still see Snell's
Law, and so on.

00:37:38.550 --> 00:37:40.720
But of course, you see
these additional phenomena,

00:37:40.720 --> 00:37:44.930
like all the electrons, which
you don't see in light beams.

00:37:44.930 --> 00:37:46.100
So you're absolutely right.

00:37:46.100 --> 00:37:50.480
There's some
significant differences

00:37:50.480 --> 00:37:51.950
which are very important.

00:37:51.950 --> 00:37:56.260
But there's also some
very, very dominant

00:37:56.260 --> 00:37:57.970
and prominent commonalities.

00:37:57.970 --> 00:38:00.100
The same goes for
light and sound.

00:38:00.100 --> 00:38:06.585
And our department recently
merged with ocean engineering.

00:38:06.585 --> 00:38:07.960
And in ocean
engineering, there's

00:38:07.960 --> 00:38:10.270
a lot of professors
who do acoustics.

00:38:10.270 --> 00:38:12.620
So as a result, I
started sitting in--

00:38:12.620 --> 00:38:14.110
at the beginning,
out of curiosity,

00:38:14.110 --> 00:38:16.360
I started sitting in a couple
of the acoustic classes.

00:38:16.360 --> 00:38:21.580
And also, this year, I sat in
the doctoral exam in acoustics.

00:38:21.580 --> 00:38:23.730
And I was surprised to
see the same terms--

00:38:23.730 --> 00:38:28.420
diffraction, refraction,
Snell's law, waveguiding,

00:38:28.420 --> 00:38:31.000
all of these things, they
happen in acoustics as well.

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:33.220
So you could say the
same thing about sound.

00:38:33.220 --> 00:38:36.130
To some approximation,
sound effects

00:38:36.130 --> 00:38:40.120
are identical to optics,
identical to light diffraction.

00:38:40.120 --> 00:38:43.120
But there's also cases of
interaction between sound

00:38:43.120 --> 00:38:46.120
and matter that is radically
different than interaction

00:38:46.120 --> 00:38:47.710
between light and matter.

00:38:47.710 --> 00:38:50.535
For example, I think it
is impossible for sound

00:38:50.535 --> 00:38:52.000
to ionize matter.

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:53.650
Light can ionize matter.

00:38:53.650 --> 00:38:57.460
I think sound has to be pretty
darn strong to ionize, right?

00:38:57.460 --> 00:39:02.230
So there are significant
differences, but also some very

00:39:02.230 --> 00:39:03.690
convenient commonalities.

00:39:03.690 --> 00:39:06.800
So all of a sudden, by studying
one field, all of a sudden,

00:39:06.800 --> 00:39:09.100
you discover that you can
understand quite a bit

00:39:09.100 --> 00:39:10.608
about a different field.

00:39:10.608 --> 00:39:11.650
So that's kind of useful.

00:39:14.480 --> 00:39:15.765
Any other questions?

00:39:22.900 --> 00:39:27.960
Let's start by saying a few
things about what is light.

00:39:27.960 --> 00:39:30.260
So light is actually
a form of energy.

00:39:30.260 --> 00:39:34.235
Really that's the simplest--
that's the only correct way

00:39:34.235 --> 00:39:35.450
to describe it.

00:39:35.450 --> 00:39:37.820
It is a form of energy
that is transmitted

00:39:37.820 --> 00:39:40.160
as an electromagnetic wave.

00:39:40.160 --> 00:39:43.170
That's a quite
correct description.

00:39:43.170 --> 00:39:46.490
But as I said before, you can
think of it either as particles

00:39:46.490 --> 00:39:48.360
or as waves.

00:39:48.360 --> 00:39:53.220
So the particles are
officially called photons.

00:39:53.220 --> 00:39:58.940
And what is a photon is actually
not an easy thing to describe.

00:39:58.940 --> 00:40:01.070
Various scientists
over the centuries

00:40:01.070 --> 00:40:03.860
fought over the
definition of a photon.

00:40:03.860 --> 00:40:05.930
And we certainly don't
want to go into quantum

00:40:05.930 --> 00:40:07.880
optics in this class.

00:40:07.880 --> 00:40:11.150
So we'll think of photons
in a very simple-minded way,

00:40:11.150 --> 00:40:14.120
as bullets that carry energy--

00:40:14.120 --> 00:40:20.630
a very small amount of energy,
as we'll see in a second--

00:40:20.630 --> 00:40:25.020
and they follow
certain trajectories.

00:40:25.020 --> 00:40:27.860
So the trajectories
we'll call rays.

00:40:27.860 --> 00:40:32.250
And I will describe these
rays a little bit later.

00:40:32.250 --> 00:40:36.380
Now, the photon, one thing that
the photons do have in common

00:40:36.380 --> 00:40:37.340
is their speed.

00:40:37.340 --> 00:40:40.310
It is, of course, the speed
of light, which, in a vacuum,

00:40:40.310 --> 00:40:46.080
is the familiar 3 times 10
to the 8 meters per second.

00:40:46.080 --> 00:40:48.060
How much energy they carry?

00:40:48.060 --> 00:40:53.230
Well, the amount of energy is
given by Planck's constant,

00:40:53.230 --> 00:41:00.360
which is a very small amount of
6.6 10 to the minus 34 joules

00:41:00.360 --> 00:41:03.920
times second, and then
multiplied by a frequency.

00:41:03.920 --> 00:41:06.490
OK, so the frequency
is, of course, hertz.

00:41:06.490 --> 00:41:07.710
So the units work out.

00:41:07.710 --> 00:41:12.570
The product over
there is energy.

00:41:12.570 --> 00:41:13.680
What is the frequency?

00:41:13.680 --> 00:41:15.380
Where does it come about?

00:41:15.380 --> 00:41:18.900
Well, to really justify the
presence of a frequency there,

00:41:18.900 --> 00:41:20.130
I have to see it.

00:41:20.130 --> 00:41:22.500
I have to go, actually,
to the other way

00:41:22.500 --> 00:41:26.430
of describing light, which is
as an electromagnetic wave.

00:41:26.430 --> 00:41:31.200
And of course, the name
"wave" implies some sort

00:41:31.200 --> 00:41:34.120
of oscillatory motion.

00:41:34.120 --> 00:41:36.420
So the horizontal axis
here is the direction

00:41:36.420 --> 00:41:38.050
of the propagation of the light.

00:41:38.050 --> 00:41:41.550
So the light is propagating
from the left to the right.

00:41:41.550 --> 00:41:43.140
What is the vertical axis?

00:41:43.140 --> 00:41:46.050
The vertical axis is an
electric field, actually.

00:41:46.050 --> 00:41:48.870
It is the same spot that you
have in a capacitor where

00:41:48.870 --> 00:41:50.460
you charge it.

00:41:50.460 --> 00:41:53.020
So it is convenient to describe
it as an electric field.

00:41:53.020 --> 00:41:55.920
You can also describe
it is a magnetic field--

00:41:55.920 --> 00:42:00.690
the same stuff that you see when
you have a refrigerator magnet.

00:42:00.690 --> 00:42:03.980
You can put either quantity
over here in the vertical axis

00:42:03.980 --> 00:42:07.470
because there are a couple
of electromagnetic fields by,

00:42:07.470 --> 00:42:10.500
as the name suggests, it
is a coupled oscillation

00:42:10.500 --> 00:42:12.973
of electric and magnetic fields.

00:42:12.973 --> 00:42:14.640
For now, let's stick
to electric fields.

00:42:14.640 --> 00:42:18.030
In this class, I will say very
little about magnetic fields.

00:42:18.030 --> 00:42:22.110
When I describe light as
a wave, I will by default

00:42:22.110 --> 00:42:24.960
refer to an electric field, OK?

00:42:24.960 --> 00:42:29.270
So light is an electric
field that oscillates

00:42:29.270 --> 00:42:31.370
as a function of position.

00:42:31.370 --> 00:42:34.870
And of course, a
wave is not static.

00:42:34.870 --> 00:42:38.590
You, all of you, have seen
waves in the Singapore

00:42:38.590 --> 00:42:40.930
Harbor, the Singapore River.

00:42:40.930 --> 00:42:43.510
You cannot see waves on the
Charles right now because it is

00:42:43.510 --> 00:42:44.570
frozen.

00:42:44.570 --> 00:42:46.630
But during more
normal times, you

00:42:46.630 --> 00:42:47.910
can see waves on the Charles.

00:42:47.910 --> 00:42:52.660
So you know a wave implies
both a spatial structure--

00:42:52.660 --> 00:42:54.430
if you look at the
picture of a wave,

00:42:54.430 --> 00:42:58.690
you see oscillatory
in the picture--

00:42:58.690 --> 00:43:01.510
but also time, because
a wave travels in time.

00:43:01.510 --> 00:43:05.570
So in the context here,
the time valuable--

00:43:05.570 --> 00:43:07.540
well, OK, I'll
[INAUDIBLE] that back.

00:43:07.540 --> 00:43:09.880
But after some time
lapse, the wave

00:43:09.880 --> 00:43:13.270
will actually move a
little bit further, OK?

00:43:13.270 --> 00:43:17.080
So this is the sense of
the wave propagation.

00:43:17.080 --> 00:43:21.140
So since you have an
oscillatory quantity here,

00:43:21.140 --> 00:43:23.920
the period is called
the wavelength--

00:43:23.920 --> 00:43:25.900
the period in the space domain.

00:43:25.900 --> 00:43:30.820
So the distance between two
peaks of the electric field

00:43:30.820 --> 00:43:33.520
oscillator there would
define it as a wavelength.

00:43:33.520 --> 00:43:38.260
And it is related to the
frequency, this quantity that

00:43:38.260 --> 00:43:41.470
enters in the particle
description of light uses

00:43:41.470 --> 00:43:43.030
this equation here.

00:43:43.030 --> 00:43:45.040
The speed of light
equals the product

00:43:45.040 --> 00:43:48.765
of the wavelength
times the frequency.

00:43:48.765 --> 00:43:50.150
So we'll do the
calculation here.

