00:51:05.710 --> 00:51:06.960
And at first, I was horrified.

00:51:06.960 --> 00:51:10.230
But then I realized he had a
point-- that very often, it

00:51:10.230 --> 00:51:13.470
is pointless to do exact
calculations if you're

00:51:13.470 --> 00:51:15.420
looking for an order
of magnitude result.

00:51:15.420 --> 00:51:18.082
For example, is the bullet
going to crash into a wall,

00:51:18.082 --> 00:51:19.290
or is it going to go through?

00:51:19.290 --> 00:51:20.820
Is it going to go back, or what?

00:51:20.820 --> 00:51:22.612
For that, you don't
need the exact numbers.

00:51:22.612 --> 00:51:27.193
Of course, exact numbers are
valuable in some other cases.

00:51:27.193 --> 00:51:28.610
It's kind of an
interesting skill,

00:51:28.610 --> 00:51:31.370
to know when to do
an half-calculation

00:51:31.370 --> 00:51:34.190
and when to do an exact
calculation, and what

00:51:34.190 --> 00:51:36.710
level of accuracy
you need, depending

00:51:36.710 --> 00:51:39.153
on the resources that you
have, the time that you have,

00:51:39.153 --> 00:51:41.320
the nature of the answer
you're looking for, and on,

00:51:41.320 --> 00:51:43.560
and so forth.

