00:55:35.673 --> 00:55:36.590
What is a battlefront?

00:55:36.590 --> 00:55:39.650
It's the people who are
unlucky enough to have

00:55:39.650 --> 00:55:42.590
been picked to be at the
frontline of the battle.

00:55:42.590 --> 00:55:47.780
So if you've seen all these old,
horrible movies about battles

00:55:47.780 --> 00:55:49.640
in the Middle Ages,
you see all these guys

00:55:49.640 --> 00:55:51.795
with their shields going ahead.

00:55:51.795 --> 00:55:54.020
And that's a
battlefront, moving.

00:55:54.020 --> 00:55:56.150
So a wavefront is
a similar concept.

00:55:56.150 --> 00:56:01.040
You have a front that is moving
as the energy of the wave

00:56:01.040 --> 00:56:04.060
is propagating.

00:56:04.060 --> 00:56:06.060
So it's perhaps not a
very interesting wavefront

00:56:06.060 --> 00:56:08.250
because it is
one-dimensional, right?

00:56:08.250 --> 00:56:11.610
The wave is propagating
along a sort of linear axis.

00:56:11.610 --> 00:56:15.780
In a second, I will show you
more interesting wavefronts

00:56:15.780 --> 00:56:19.753
that are of relevance
in this class.

00:56:19.753 --> 00:56:21.420
The other thing I
want to point out here

00:56:21.420 --> 00:56:24.660
is, again, I want to bring up
the concept of the wavelength.

00:56:24.660 --> 00:56:26.730
And we defined the
wavelength already

00:56:26.730 --> 00:56:29.070
as the distance
between two peaks.

00:56:29.070 --> 00:56:31.200
So if you look at
two peaks over here,

00:56:31.200 --> 00:56:34.080
the distance is, by
definition, of a wavelength.

00:56:34.080 --> 00:56:37.140
But also, the wavelength,
it has a different meaning.

00:56:37.140 --> 00:56:39.540
If you look at it from the
point of view of propagation

00:56:39.540 --> 00:56:42.150
of the wave, it is
also the distance

00:56:42.150 --> 00:56:45.240
that the wave propagated in--

00:56:45.240 --> 00:56:46.020
how long?

00:56:46.020 --> 00:56:48.660
Well, one period, right?

00:56:48.660 --> 00:56:50.400
And in fact, this is
where the equation c

00:56:50.400 --> 00:56:52.140
equals lambda nu comes from.

00:56:58.780 --> 00:57:00.830
I'll let you do
that as a homework.

00:57:00.830 --> 00:57:04.720
But if you think about
it, if you treat the wave

00:57:04.720 --> 00:57:11.030
as a particle that
took 3 seconds to move

00:57:11.030 --> 00:57:15.520
lambda units of distance,
then its velocity c

00:57:15.520 --> 00:57:18.520
must obey this
equation over here.

00:57:18.520 --> 00:57:21.310
It's a one-line
derivation kind of thing.

00:57:21.310 --> 00:57:22.910
I'll let you do
it as a homework.

00:57:22.910 --> 00:57:25.630
And also, I want to
emphasize that this equation

00:57:25.630 --> 00:57:30.340
that we called the spatial
relation in the previous slide,

00:57:30.340 --> 00:57:33.460
it is only true if light
propagates in free space

00:57:33.460 --> 00:57:35.110
or in uniform media.

00:57:35.110 --> 00:57:39.268
If you put light, for
example, in a confined space,

00:57:39.268 --> 00:57:41.560
this equation changes, and
it becomes a little bit more

00:57:41.560 --> 00:57:43.360
complicated.

00:57:43.360 --> 00:57:46.600
But in this class, we don't
deal with this phenomenon.

00:57:46.600 --> 00:57:49.690
If you want to learn about
more complicated dispersion

00:57:49.690 --> 00:57:52.930
relations, you will have to
take Professor Fujimoto's class

00:57:52.930 --> 00:57:55.600
in electrical engineering.

00:57:55.600 --> 00:57:57.780
I might mention something
like this in passing,

00:57:57.780 --> 00:57:59.520
but not in great detail.

00:57:59.520 --> 00:58:01.080
For this, we will
be happy enough

00:58:01.080 --> 00:58:05.950
to take this as a dispersion
equation of the light.

00:58:05.950 --> 00:58:07.950
But again, I want to alert
you that there's also

00:58:07.950 --> 00:58:12.900
other dispersion
relations that may occur.

00:58:12.900 --> 00:58:15.970
OK, the other thing that I will
not spend too much time here,

00:58:15.970 --> 00:58:20.880
but it will come up later with
great force and great detail

00:58:20.880 --> 00:58:23.600
is the concept of phase delay.

00:58:23.600 --> 00:58:28.190
So you probably remember this
from your trigonometry class.

00:58:28.190 --> 00:58:30.500
If you have a
periodic phenomenon

00:58:30.500 --> 00:58:34.430
or a periodic function, you can
pick an arbitrary point in time

00:58:34.430 --> 00:58:36.200
and call it your reference.

00:58:36.200 --> 00:58:38.390
And then, as the
phenomenon evolves,

00:58:38.390 --> 00:58:43.890
you can refer to this initial
point as if with a phase delay.

00:58:43.890 --> 00:58:46.760
So the phase delay
is relative to 2pi,

00:58:46.760 --> 00:58:49.310
which measures one full cycle.

00:58:49.310 --> 00:58:54.590
So then you can interpret
these snapshots over here

00:58:54.590 --> 00:58:58.850
as phase-delayed versions
of the original wave.

00:58:58.850 --> 00:59:04.580
So for example, between
0 and 1/8 of a period,

00:59:04.580 --> 00:59:08.660
your phase delay equals pi
over 4, because 2pi over 8

00:59:08.660 --> 00:59:10.460
equals pi over 4.

00:59:10.460 --> 00:59:13.190
So this is a concept that
will come up again, as I said,

00:59:13.190 --> 00:59:14.550
in great detail.

00:59:14.550 --> 00:59:19.620
I just wanted you to be a little
bit aware of it right now.

00:59:19.620 --> 00:59:23.280
What I really wanted
to emphasize over here

00:59:23.280 --> 00:59:26.380
is that light does not
usually propagate along

00:59:26.380 --> 00:59:30.150
an exact one line, as I
showed in a previous line,

00:59:30.150 --> 00:59:31.770
but it propagates in 3D space.

00:59:31.770 --> 00:59:33.040
So it can expand.

00:59:33.040 --> 00:59:34.040
It can contract.

00:59:34.040 --> 00:59:36.450
It can do weird things, right?

00:59:36.450 --> 00:59:38.340
So to do that, we
need a slightly more

00:59:38.340 --> 00:59:39.360
elaborate description.

00:59:39.360 --> 00:59:43.017
So this is an attempt
to plot 3D space.

00:59:43.017 --> 00:59:45.100
And if you think about the
wavefront in this case,

00:59:45.100 --> 00:59:48.390
it is a surface
that moves from left

00:59:48.390 --> 00:59:51.240
to right as a function of time.

00:59:51.240 --> 00:59:54.292
So as the wavefront propagates,
the surface is moving.

00:59:54.292 --> 00:59:56.000
By the way, this is
a fictitious surface.

00:59:56.000 --> 00:59:59.220
I'm not thinking of a
physical surface or anything.

00:59:59.220 --> 01:00:03.680
But if you think about the
energy that the light carries,

01:00:03.680 --> 01:00:07.430
the energy is actually moving
as the wave propagates.

01:00:07.430 --> 01:00:09.410
This is how you can
connect the two.

01:00:09.410 --> 01:00:11.200
If you go out to the Charles--

01:00:11.200 --> 01:00:13.970
OK, you have to wait until
April when it unfreezes--

01:00:13.970 --> 01:00:16.990
but if you look at the
waves on the water--

01:00:16.990 --> 01:00:19.490
of course, you can do it at
home on your bucket or something

01:00:19.490 --> 01:00:20.130
like that--

01:00:20.130 --> 01:00:22.630
but if you look at the waves,
there's also a physical sense,

01:00:22.630 --> 01:00:24.770
because the water
wave, there's a crest.

01:00:24.770 --> 01:00:26.420
So there wavefront
of the water wave

01:00:26.420 --> 01:00:30.687
is the crest that moves
as the wave propagates.

01:00:33.320 --> 01:00:37.800
So these surfaces, the weapons,
they can have different shapes.

01:00:37.800 --> 01:00:40.490
They cannot have arbitrary
shapes because they're governed

01:00:40.490 --> 01:00:43.880
by the laws of
light propagation.

01:00:43.880 --> 01:00:48.860
But certain allowable shapes
turn out to be very simple,

01:00:48.860 --> 01:00:50.930
and we will be dealing
with them a lot.

01:00:50.930 --> 01:00:53.480
So the simplest is
a planar wavefront

01:00:53.480 --> 01:00:56.960
that, as the name
implies, is a plane.

01:00:56.960 --> 01:01:00.260
And the next simple is
a spherical wavefront,

01:01:00.260 --> 01:01:03.450
which, again, as the name
implies, is a sphere.

01:01:03.450 --> 01:01:08.330
So you can think those as
our two major wavefronts

01:01:08.330 --> 01:01:10.770
that we'll be dealing with
throughout the class--

01:01:10.770 --> 01:01:12.830
the planar wavefront
and the spherical.

01:01:12.830 --> 01:01:14.980
And we'll-- yes.

01:01:14.980 --> 01:01:17.530
AUDIENCE: So in the last slide,
you showed the electric field

01:01:17.530 --> 01:01:18.760
as being the y-axis.

01:01:18.760 --> 01:01:21.070
But here, it's space, not field.

01:01:24.030 --> 01:01:26.790
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Yes, so
that is correct, and thank you.

01:01:26.790 --> 01:01:28.620
And I should relabel the slide.

01:01:28.620 --> 01:01:34.380
Here, the two axes, they
correspond to x and y,

01:01:34.380 --> 01:01:36.370
the space coordinates, yeah.

01:01:36.370 --> 01:01:40.200
And the electric field is not
found here because I cannot

01:01:40.200 --> 01:01:42.100
plot a fourth dimension.

01:01:42.100 --> 01:01:45.750
So what is happening here is the
electric field is maximum at t

01:01:45.750 --> 01:01:47.230
equal to 0.

01:01:47.230 --> 01:01:51.690
So at t equals 0, the electric
field is maximum on this plane.

01:01:51.690 --> 01:01:54.630
If you wait 1/8 of
a period, the field

01:01:54.630 --> 01:01:56.220
will be maximum at this plane.

01:01:56.220 --> 01:01:58.620
If you wait another
1/8 of a period,

01:01:58.620 --> 01:02:00.540
the field is maximum
on this plane.

01:02:00.540 --> 01:02:03.090
So the wavefront, in
this case, is the maximum

01:02:03.090 --> 01:02:04.290
of the electric field--

01:02:04.290 --> 01:02:06.480
the crest, if you wish,
of the electric field--

01:02:06.480 --> 01:02:08.740
as it propagates through space.

01:02:08.740 --> 01:02:10.790
And the same is here.

01:02:10.790 --> 01:02:14.990
Again, these surfaces mean
that the field is maximum

01:02:14.990 --> 01:02:17.160
on the surface at t equals 0.

01:02:17.160 --> 01:02:19.340
And then, 1/8 of a
period later, the field

01:02:19.340 --> 01:02:22.660
is maximum on the surface,
and so on, and so forth.

01:02:22.660 --> 01:02:23.260
Thanks, yeah.

01:02:23.260 --> 01:02:28.020
So that's a very
important clarification.

01:02:28.020 --> 01:02:31.400
Now, what do you think
should happen to the energy

01:02:31.400 --> 01:02:34.370
density in the two cases?

01:02:34.370 --> 01:02:36.170
Suppose I have a
fixed amount of energy

01:02:36.170 --> 01:02:40.438
that is entered in on the left.

01:02:40.438 --> 01:02:41.730
Are they different in some way?

01:02:41.730 --> 01:02:43.387
Yeah.

01:02:43.387 --> 01:02:45.543
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:02:45.543 --> 01:02:46.960
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
That's right.

01:02:46.960 --> 01:02:50.280
Can I can ask you to push
the button and repeat that?

01:02:50.280 --> 01:02:52.290
Yeah.

01:02:52.290 --> 01:02:55.170
AUDIENCE: The plane
wave's energy is constant,

01:02:55.170 --> 01:02:58.050
energy density is constant,
and the spherical wave's energy

01:02:58.050 --> 01:02:59.582
density is smaller.

01:02:59.582 --> 01:03:00.790
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Correct.

01:03:00.790 --> 01:03:01.720
AUDIENCE: As it expands.

01:03:01.720 --> 01:03:03.137
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Correct, yes,

01:03:03.137 --> 01:03:04.990
because energy has
to be concerned.

01:03:04.990 --> 01:03:10.410
So in this case, the
wavefront is invariant,

01:03:10.410 --> 01:03:12.360
so the energy must
remain constant.

01:03:12.360 --> 01:03:14.520
In this case, the
wavefront is expanding,

01:03:14.520 --> 01:03:19.270
so the energy density will
decrease as you go away.

01:03:19.270 --> 01:03:21.360
We will make this
more precise later.

01:03:21.360 --> 01:03:23.590
We'll define what we
mean by energy density.

01:03:23.590 --> 01:03:25.710
In fact, it is called intensity.

01:03:25.710 --> 01:03:28.420
So we'll define that.

01:03:28.420 --> 01:03:30.390
So basically if you
measure the energy

01:03:30.390 --> 01:03:34.500
in watts per area, watts
per centimeter square,

01:03:34.500 --> 01:03:36.630
in this case, it has
to decrease in order

01:03:36.630 --> 01:03:38.640
to make sure that the
energy you started

01:03:38.640 --> 01:03:44.190
with at the center of the
sphere is preserved throughout.

01:03:44.190 --> 01:03:46.800
The next concept I would
like to define is the ray.

01:03:46.800 --> 01:03:49.140
And the reason we
introduced wavefronts

01:03:49.140 --> 01:03:53.550
is primarily because I wanted
to define relatively precisely,

01:03:53.550 --> 01:03:56.550
now, what I mean by a ray.

01:03:56.550 --> 01:04:00.470
For the next 4 weeks, we will be
talking about rays exclusively,

01:04:00.470 --> 01:04:02.070
OK?

01:04:02.070 --> 01:04:05.160
So a ray is basically a
normal to the wavefront.

01:04:05.160 --> 01:04:08.670
That is the correct,
accurate definition of a ray.

01:04:08.670 --> 01:04:11.820
You take this surfaces,
you plug the normals,

01:04:11.820 --> 01:04:13.807
and these lines are the rays.

01:04:13.807 --> 01:04:15.390
So in this case, the
rays are parallel

01:04:15.390 --> 01:04:18.360
because all the surfaces
are parallel planes.

01:04:18.360 --> 01:04:20.910
In this case, the
rays form a fan,

01:04:20.910 --> 01:04:23.680
like a divergent
fan, that attaches

01:04:23.680 --> 01:04:27.270
at each point on the spheres.

01:04:27.270 --> 01:04:31.280
The fan components are
normal to the surfaces.

01:04:31.280 --> 01:04:34.230
And you can also think
of them as trajectories

01:04:34.230 --> 01:04:39.846
over which the particles
of light propagate.

01:04:39.846 --> 01:04:41.590
It is not, perhaps,
very accurate

01:04:41.590 --> 01:04:44.200
to think of the particles
as photons in this case.

01:04:44.200 --> 01:04:47.740
So think of them as some sort
of fictitious light bullets that

01:04:47.740 --> 01:04:52.370
propagate down the
ray trajectories.

01:04:52.370 --> 01:04:54.020
And the rays have
several properties,

01:04:54.020 --> 01:04:57.050
which I will ratify
later in the class.

01:04:57.050 --> 01:04:59.800
The rays have to be continuous
in piecewise differential.

01:04:59.800 --> 01:05:01.480
A ray cannot jump, for example.

01:05:01.480 --> 01:05:04.430
You cannot have a ray
that looks like this.

01:05:12.910 --> 01:05:14.836
That cannot happen-- forbidden.

01:05:18.724 --> 01:05:26.440
A ray can have a continuous
but, perhaps, not differentiable

01:05:26.440 --> 01:05:27.410
band like this.

01:05:27.410 --> 01:05:28.700
So that's allowed.

01:05:28.700 --> 01:05:31.150
And it can also have a
smooth, continuous path.

01:05:31.150 --> 01:05:33.190
That's also allowed.

01:05:33.190 --> 01:05:35.970
OK, that is, obviously,
why it is forbidden.

01:05:35.970 --> 01:05:39.190
It is kind of strange to
imagine the photon disappearing

01:05:39.190 --> 01:05:40.650
and appearing again
someplace else.

01:05:44.260 --> 01:05:48.290
The others we will
see later in action.

01:05:48.290 --> 01:05:53.670
And from our experience,
rays are straight lines.

01:05:53.670 --> 01:05:55.910
And why do we say that,
from our experience?

01:05:55.910 --> 01:05:58.200
Where have you seen
rays in everyday life?

01:06:01.320 --> 01:06:02.820
Button.

01:06:02.820 --> 01:06:03.532
AUDIENCE: Lasers.

01:06:03.532 --> 01:06:04.990
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Lasers is one.

01:06:04.990 --> 01:06:08.460
But usually, if you have the
beam coming out of a laser,

01:06:08.460 --> 01:06:12.260
it looks kind of
like a straight line.

01:06:12.260 --> 01:06:15.800
Another example, perhaps,
from even more everyday life.

01:06:15.800 --> 01:06:16.730
AUDIENCE: Shadows.

01:06:16.730 --> 01:06:18.522
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Shadows, that's right.

01:06:18.522 --> 01:06:20.240
If you look at
shadows, the light

01:06:20.240 --> 01:06:24.070
appears to come out
straight out of the shadows.

01:06:24.070 --> 01:06:26.105
So it's a little bit
strange that I drew a ray

01:06:26.105 --> 01:06:28.340
as a curved trajectory.

01:06:28.340 --> 01:06:31.250
We will see a bit later, maybe
even today if we don't run out

01:06:31.250 --> 01:06:36.590
of time, that light rays can
actually follow curved paths

01:06:36.590 --> 01:06:38.390
under certain conditions.

01:06:38.390 --> 01:06:41.810
But what is for sure, that in
free space or uniform space

01:06:41.810 --> 01:06:42.940
like air--

01:06:42.940 --> 01:06:44.990
we observe shadows in air.

01:06:44.990 --> 01:06:51.810
So air is pretty much
uniform, and for that reason,

01:06:51.810 --> 01:06:53.950
rays propagate in
straight lines.

01:06:53.950 --> 01:06:56.550
By the way, you don't have
to go too far to see examples

01:06:56.550 --> 01:06:59.280
of curved ray propagation.

01:06:59.280 --> 01:07:01.470
The best example is flicker.

01:07:01.470 --> 01:07:04.680
If you go up in the
mountains at night

01:07:04.680 --> 01:07:06.753
and you look down at
the city beneath--

01:07:06.753 --> 01:07:08.420
I don't think you can
do that in Boston.

01:07:08.420 --> 01:07:10.210
We don't have any
mountains high enough.

01:07:10.210 --> 01:07:13.140
But in Los Angeles, for
example, it's very pronounced.

01:07:13.140 --> 01:07:16.020
If you go to the Hollywood Hills
and look down, you see flicker.

01:07:16.020 --> 01:07:18.380
The lights in the city,
they are not steady.

01:07:18.380 --> 01:07:20.940
They kind of flicker.

01:07:20.940 --> 01:07:25.010
So the result of that is
because the atmosphere,

01:07:25.010 --> 01:07:26.770
it is not an exactly
uniform medium.

01:07:26.770 --> 01:07:31.250
You have temperature changes,
air currents, and so on.

01:07:31.250 --> 01:07:35.080
And because of that, the
rays between the city lights

01:07:35.080 --> 01:07:38.590
and your eye, the rays
follow a sort of curved path.

01:07:38.590 --> 01:07:40.800
Very slightly curved, but
because they propagate

01:07:40.800 --> 01:07:43.600
a long distance, it is enough
to result in this flicker

01:07:43.600 --> 01:07:45.340
phenomenon.

01:07:45.340 --> 01:07:47.270
OK, so from that--

01:07:47.270 --> 01:07:50.060
it is not quite obvious
as in the shadow--

01:07:50.060 --> 01:07:54.010
but from that, we have kind
of experienced, all of us,

01:07:54.010 --> 01:07:57.125
that the rays might
actually not propagate along

01:07:57.125 --> 01:07:58.170
a straight path.

01:07:58.170 --> 01:08:00.020
And in a second,
I will define when

01:08:00.020 --> 01:08:02.450
that happens-- when
a ray can propagate

01:08:02.450 --> 01:08:06.650
in a curved trajectory.

01:08:06.650 --> 01:08:11.770
Before I do that, I already
implied that the reason

01:08:11.770 --> 01:08:14.420
rays might do strange
things, like deviate

01:08:14.420 --> 01:08:16.109
from the straight and narrow--

01:08:16.109 --> 01:08:18.710
I'm sorry, might deviate
from the straight path--

01:08:18.710 --> 01:08:21.950
is because of interaction
with matter, right?

01:08:21.950 --> 01:08:26.120
It is the non-uniformity in
air, in my earlier example,

01:08:26.120 --> 01:08:29.670
that caused the rays to bend.

01:08:29.670 --> 01:08:33.930
So then, the next topic is
a very simple description

01:08:33.930 --> 01:08:36.240
of how light
interacts with matter.

01:08:36.240 --> 01:08:38.180
And for now, I will
say it is a fairy

01:08:38.180 --> 01:08:41.550
tale, because we don't know
enough electromagnetics yet.

01:08:41.550 --> 01:08:44.670
I will come back to this
topic after we define light

01:08:44.670 --> 01:08:47.010
as an electromagnetic wave.

01:08:47.010 --> 01:08:50.490
I will come back to this topic
and tell you more rigorously

01:08:50.490 --> 01:08:52.610
how light interacts with matter.

01:08:52.610 --> 01:08:54.420
For now, very briefly,
I will tell you

01:08:54.420 --> 01:08:58.430
that there is three
types of interaction

01:08:58.430 --> 01:09:00.410
that we'll discuss
in this class--

01:09:00.410 --> 01:09:03.470
absorption, refraction,
and scattering.

01:09:03.470 --> 01:09:06.050
So today, I will define
absorption and refraction

01:09:06.050 --> 01:09:10.600
in very simple
phenomenological terms.

01:09:10.600 --> 01:09:13.939
Anybody knows what it
means, "phenomenological"?

01:09:13.939 --> 01:09:16.729
I am Greek, so I have a
benefit of the language.

01:09:22.410 --> 01:09:25.529
"Phenomenological" means
based on observation.

01:09:25.529 --> 01:09:28.649
It means we define
this phenomenon

01:09:28.649 --> 01:09:30.569
based on what we
observe, but we don't

01:09:30.569 --> 01:09:34.470
try to dig any deeper
into the basic principles

01:09:34.470 --> 01:09:36.149
behind this phenomenon.

01:09:36.149 --> 01:09:38.290
You will see in a
second what I mean.

01:09:38.290 --> 01:09:41.779
Very well, we'll define
absorption and refraction.

01:09:41.779 --> 01:09:43.849
And what I want to
emphasize, also,

01:09:43.849 --> 01:09:46.430
is that this is not the only
three types of interactions.

01:09:46.430 --> 01:09:49.183
Light can do a lot
of other things.

01:09:49.183 --> 01:09:50.600
There's fluorescence,
that you are

01:09:50.600 --> 01:09:53.660
familiar if you go to nightclubs
where they use ultraviolet,

01:09:53.660 --> 01:09:54.260
right?

01:09:54.260 --> 01:09:55.700
People look kind of funny.

01:09:55.700 --> 01:09:58.220
That is fluorescence.

01:09:58.220 --> 01:10:01.420
There is non-linear phenomena.

01:10:01.420 --> 01:10:03.290
There's ionization
that can happen.

01:10:03.290 --> 01:10:05.360
So a lot of different
things that can happen,

01:10:05.360 --> 01:10:07.290
but I will not cover
them in this class.

01:10:07.290 --> 01:10:10.610
So as I say, they're outside
the scope of our interest here.

01:10:15.110 --> 01:10:18.140
Going on with this, let me
define absorption first.

01:10:18.140 --> 01:10:23.010
So from experience,
we know that anything

01:10:23.010 --> 01:10:26.700
that travels through a
medium suffers losses.

01:10:26.700 --> 01:10:28.140
Many of your
mechanical engineers,

01:10:28.140 --> 01:10:33.210
you know that if you have
a mechanical disturbance

01:10:33.210 --> 01:10:37.140
like sound propagating down
the medium, at the exit,

01:10:37.140 --> 01:10:39.543
you see less of the
energy that you put in.

01:10:39.543 --> 01:10:41.085
Some of you are
electrical engineers.

01:10:41.085 --> 01:10:44.310
You know that if you run
current through a device,

01:10:44.310 --> 01:10:46.230
typically, at the
exit of the device,

01:10:46.230 --> 01:10:49.990
you see less current or
less electrical energy.

01:10:49.990 --> 01:10:52.630
Typically, you see a
voltage drop than the energy

01:10:52.630 --> 01:10:54.260
that you put in.

01:10:54.260 --> 01:10:57.270
So why does this happen?

01:10:57.270 --> 01:10:58.670
Well, because of--

01:10:58.670 --> 01:10:59.170
Why?

01:10:59.170 --> 01:10:59.962
Why does it happen?

01:11:07.930 --> 01:11:08.430
Yes.

01:11:13.300 --> 01:11:14.761
[LAUGHS]

01:11:14.761 --> 01:11:16.222
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:11:16.222 --> 01:11:17.650
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
That's right.

01:11:17.650 --> 01:11:19.770
It is conversion of
energy to heat, right?

01:11:19.770 --> 01:11:22.450
And that generally is
undesirable unless--

01:11:22.450 --> 01:11:24.900
anyway, we seldom heat
ourselves with-- well,

01:11:24.900 --> 01:11:26.810
unless it's the sunlight
on a day like this,

01:11:26.810 --> 01:11:29.080
we appreciate the heating.

01:11:29.080 --> 01:11:32.980
But in Singapore, generally, we
don't appreciate the heating,

01:11:32.980 --> 01:11:36.160
because the sunlight is
too intense, typically,

01:11:36.160 --> 01:11:38.702
to tolerate.

01:11:38.702 --> 01:11:40.160
But yeah, the fact
of the matter is

01:11:40.160 --> 01:11:44.090
that there is ohmic
losses, or dissipation,

01:11:44.090 --> 01:11:48.680
like you very correctly said,
that cause a decrease in power.

01:11:48.680 --> 01:11:54.500
So the phenomenological law
that describes this effect

01:11:54.500 --> 01:11:58.430
is exponential in the length
of propagation in matter.

01:11:58.430 --> 01:12:00.800
So by "phenomenological,"
what I mean

01:12:00.800 --> 01:12:03.370
is that I throw this
equation at you,

01:12:03.370 --> 01:12:05.870
but I haven't told you why, OK?

01:12:05.870 --> 01:12:07.010
I will tell you why later.

01:12:07.010 --> 01:12:09.710
When we do electromagnetics,
I will justify

01:12:09.710 --> 01:12:11.570
why this law comes about.

01:12:11.570 --> 01:12:13.700
And strangely enough,
it is called Beer's Law.

01:12:13.700 --> 01:12:15.050
No, it's not pronounced "beer."

01:12:15.050 --> 01:12:16.400
It's pronounced "bear."

01:12:16.400 --> 01:12:17.470
This fellow was German.

01:12:17.470 --> 01:12:22.050
But anyway-- and light does
get absorbed by beer, actually.

01:12:22.050 --> 01:12:25.680
And strangely enough, I did
see a paper at a conference

01:12:25.680 --> 01:12:29.070
once where someone was measuring
the optical properties of beer.

01:12:29.070 --> 01:12:31.340
And I'm not kidding, actually.

01:12:31.340 --> 01:12:33.960
They had their project
funded by I don't know whom,

01:12:33.960 --> 01:12:37.998
to shoot laser beams through
big containers of beer.

01:12:37.998 --> 01:12:40.290
And then I don't know exactly
what they were measuring,

01:12:40.290 --> 01:12:42.720
but I thought it was a very
cleverly conceived project.

01:12:42.720 --> 01:12:45.180
Because after you finish the
experiment, what do you do?

01:12:45.180 --> 01:12:46.660
You drink the beer, right?

01:12:46.660 --> 01:12:47.160
OK.

01:12:50.360 --> 01:12:55.490
So I said that the output
energy decays exponentially

01:12:55.490 --> 01:12:57.620
as a function of the
length of the medium.

01:12:57.620 --> 01:12:59.570
The coefficient that
goes in the exponent

01:12:59.570 --> 01:13:02.090
is, again, very highly
dependent on the material

01:13:02.090 --> 01:13:03.590
that the light propagates.

01:13:03.590 --> 01:13:06.380
Conductors-- like
metals-- they tend

01:13:06.380 --> 01:13:07.800
to have very high dissipation.

01:13:07.800 --> 01:13:11.390
If you might propagate a few
microns inside the metal,

01:13:11.390 --> 01:13:12.770
the light is all lost.

01:13:12.770 --> 01:13:14.810
It is all converted to heat.

01:13:14.810 --> 01:13:17.732
So on the other hand,
the electrics like glass,

01:13:17.732 --> 01:13:19.190
they can have very
low dissipation.

01:13:19.190 --> 01:13:23.780
In fact, some materials,
they use some special glasses

01:13:23.780 --> 01:13:27.860
in optical fibers that
they usually transmit light

01:13:27.860 --> 01:13:29.552
over very long distances.

01:13:29.552 --> 01:13:31.010
In these occasions,
the dissipation

01:13:31.010 --> 01:13:34.860
is in the order of a fraction
of a dB per kilometer.

01:13:34.860 --> 01:13:37.460
So it is I don't know how many
orders of magnitude there,

01:13:37.460 --> 01:13:41.540
around eight or nine orders of
magnitude in the dissipation

01:13:41.540 --> 01:13:42.890
coefficient.

01:13:42.890 --> 01:13:45.020
And again, that
depends on the way

01:13:45.020 --> 01:13:46.760
light interacts with matter.

01:13:46.760 --> 01:13:49.480
I will say a little bit
more about that later.

01:13:49.480 --> 01:13:53.645
But for now, again,
take me to my word.

01:13:53.645 --> 01:13:55.520
Never take anybody to
their word, by the way.

01:13:55.520 --> 01:13:58.705
But I think for
reasons of organizing

01:13:58.705 --> 01:14:00.080
the presentation
of the material,

01:14:00.080 --> 01:14:05.090
sometimes I will ask you to
take my word for granted.

01:14:05.090 --> 01:14:07.190
And usually, when I
ask you to do that,

01:14:07.190 --> 01:14:11.140
I will come back and justify
myself perhaps a few lectures

01:14:11.140 --> 01:14:13.600
later, or something like that.

01:14:13.600 --> 01:14:16.960
OK, and the other thing
I want to emphasize

01:14:16.960 --> 01:14:20.740
is that dissipation or
absorption depends strongly

01:14:20.740 --> 01:14:21.910
on the wavelength.

01:14:21.910 --> 01:14:24.490
And that, again, goes back to
what we were saying before.

01:14:24.490 --> 01:14:27.430
Different wavelengths
carry different energy,

01:14:27.430 --> 01:14:29.110
and different energies
of the photons,

01:14:29.110 --> 01:14:31.530
they will interact with the
matter in different ways.

01:14:31.530 --> 01:14:33.280
They might [INAUDIBLE]
due to oscillation.

01:14:33.280 --> 01:14:36.850
They might set it into
dipole polarization.

01:14:36.850 --> 01:14:40.620
They might set matter, they
might ionize it-- whatever.

01:14:40.620 --> 01:14:43.490
So depending on who happens,
you get different behavior.

01:14:43.490 --> 01:14:46.790
So this is the atmosphere.

01:14:46.790 --> 01:14:49.140
The percent of transmission--
not exactly the alpha

01:14:49.140 --> 01:14:54.210
coefficient, but a transmission,
percent transmission throughout

01:14:54.210 --> 01:14:55.380
a nominal length--

01:14:55.380 --> 01:15:01.030
I believe it is in the
order of over a few meters--

01:15:01.030 --> 01:15:03.020
as a function of wavelength.

01:15:03.020 --> 01:15:04.900
So we can see that
it varies quite a bit

01:15:04.900 --> 01:15:07.180
even within the visible range.

01:15:07.180 --> 01:15:09.850
The atmosphere is not
completely transparent.

01:15:09.850 --> 01:15:12.340
It is a little bit
less transparent

01:15:12.340 --> 01:15:17.185
at blue wavelengths.

01:15:17.185 --> 01:15:20.830
It becomes, then,
almost transparent

01:15:20.830 --> 01:15:22.530
at the longer wavelengths.

01:15:22.530 --> 01:15:26.025
And then-- this
is infrared now--

01:15:26.025 --> 01:15:27.400
in the infrared,
you see you have

01:15:27.400 --> 01:15:30.735
some very strong absorption.

01:15:30.735 --> 01:15:32.360
The transmission
coefficient goes down.

01:15:32.360 --> 01:15:34.030
That means strong
absorption here.

01:15:34.030 --> 01:15:36.680
That actually has to do
with molecular resonances.

01:15:36.680 --> 01:15:40.270
And you can think of molecules
as little mass spring damper

01:15:40.270 --> 01:15:41.200
systems.

01:15:41.200 --> 01:15:42.790
And the photon comes
in and kicks them

01:15:42.790 --> 01:15:44.868
so it sets them
into oscillation.

01:15:44.868 --> 01:15:46.660
When that happens, the
energy of the photon

01:15:46.660 --> 01:15:50.080
gets transformed resonantly
into the molecule,

01:15:50.080 --> 01:15:51.530
and then you get loss.

01:15:51.530 --> 01:15:54.760
So in this case, it is a
little bit more complicated

01:15:54.760 --> 01:15:57.940
than heating, than
simple heating.

01:15:57.940 --> 01:15:59.680
But the net effect
is still the same.

01:15:59.680 --> 01:16:02.715
You still get heating from
the motion of these molecules.

01:16:02.715 --> 01:16:04.090
But anyway, that's
the reason why

01:16:04.090 --> 01:16:08.140
you get these strong
absorption maxima over here.

01:16:11.800 --> 01:16:15.190
What I really wanted to
get to today so that we

01:16:15.190 --> 01:16:17.110
can progress with
geometrical optics

01:16:17.110 --> 01:16:20.870
is the phenomenon of refraction.

01:16:20.870 --> 01:16:23.880
So refraction, is-- is
refers to, actually,

01:16:23.880 --> 01:16:25.440
a rather strange
thing that, again, I

01:16:25.440 --> 01:16:28.470
will ask you to take for
granted until we talk

01:16:28.470 --> 01:16:30.910
in detail about polarization.

01:16:30.910 --> 01:16:34.200
And that is the fact
that the speed of light

01:16:34.200 --> 01:16:37.500
changes when light
enters the material.

01:16:37.500 --> 01:16:40.110
In this case, we're talking
primarily about dielectrics,

01:16:40.110 --> 01:16:41.957
but it's also true for metals.

01:16:41.957 --> 01:16:44.290
But of course, in metals, the
light doesn't go very far.

01:16:44.290 --> 01:16:47.830
So OK, the speed changes,
but it doesn't go very far.

01:16:47.830 --> 01:16:51.180
In dielectrics, the
light can go quite far,

01:16:51.180 --> 01:16:52.690
but its speed is different.

01:16:52.690 --> 01:16:57.210
And again, phenomenologically--
without describing the physical

01:16:57.210 --> 01:16:59.710
origins of why--

01:16:59.710 --> 01:17:02.260
the speed is, of
course, reduced,

01:17:02.260 --> 01:17:04.150
and it's used by
a constant that is

01:17:04.150 --> 01:17:07.540
known as index of refraction,
or refractive index.

01:17:07.540 --> 01:17:13.900
And most books use the
symbol n to denote it.

01:17:13.900 --> 01:17:17.650
And the value of
n can value a lot.

01:17:17.650 --> 01:17:21.400
In a vacuum, n equals exactly 1.

01:17:21.400 --> 01:17:24.870
So the speed of light in
vacuum equals exactly c.

01:17:24.870 --> 01:17:28.600
In air, it is close to 1,
within two significant digits.

01:17:28.600 --> 01:17:32.260
It's maybe 1.005 or
something like that.

01:17:32.260 --> 01:17:34.790
And it depends also on the
temperature, the pressure,

01:17:34.790 --> 01:17:38.700
a number of different
properties over the air,

01:17:38.700 --> 01:17:41.970
as we'll see again later.

01:17:41.970 --> 01:17:44.220
And then, typical
dielectrics that we see

01:17:44.220 --> 01:17:45.750
are water, of course.

01:17:45.750 --> 01:17:48.840
So then, why is it
the water interesting?

01:17:48.840 --> 01:17:51.120
Well, because-- well, water.

01:17:51.120 --> 01:17:54.110
But also because our bodies
are composed mostly of water.

01:17:54.110 --> 01:17:57.900
Our tissue is approximately
70% or 75% water.

01:17:57.900 --> 01:18:00.720
So light index of
refraction in a body

01:18:00.720 --> 01:18:04.050
is also equal to the
same quantity, 1.3.

01:18:04.050 --> 01:18:07.140
Actually, this would
be 1.33, if you really

01:18:07.140 --> 01:18:08.750
want to be more accurate.

01:18:08.750 --> 01:18:11.640
And glass-- so glass
is used in pretty much

01:18:11.640 --> 01:18:14.880
every optical instrument
for visible wavelengths.

01:18:14.880 --> 01:18:16.470
So in glass, the
index of refraction

01:18:16.470 --> 01:18:21.390
is approximately 1.5.

01:18:21.390 --> 01:18:24.810
OK what does this mean now,
the speed of light changes?

01:18:24.810 --> 01:18:28.490
Another way to say it is that
the wavelength of the light

01:18:28.490 --> 01:18:29.320
changes.

01:18:29.320 --> 01:18:32.750
And this is actually
a more proper way

01:18:32.750 --> 01:18:35.030
to think of the phenomenon.

01:18:35.030 --> 01:18:37.310
When we'll do
electromagnetics, we'll

01:18:37.310 --> 01:18:40.850
see that the change
in speed is actually

01:18:40.850 --> 01:18:44.050
derived from that observation.

01:18:44.050 --> 01:18:49.940
And the way the wavelength
changes is it becomes shorter.

01:18:49.940 --> 01:18:53.240
So if you have a light happily
propagating in free space,

01:18:53.240 --> 01:18:54.710
and then, all of
a sudden, there's

01:18:54.710 --> 01:18:58.850
an abrupt interface and
light enters a dielectric,

01:18:58.850 --> 01:19:01.048
the wavelengths becomes shorter.

01:19:01.048 --> 01:19:02.090
Now, what does that mean?

01:19:02.090 --> 01:19:05.680
Does this mean that, for
example, if I have red light,

01:19:05.680 --> 01:19:12.050
and the red light goes into
glass, the light becomes green?

01:19:12.050 --> 01:19:14.980
That's actually not
what we observe, right?

01:19:14.980 --> 01:19:21.040
if you observe, many
of you have seen,

01:19:21.040 --> 01:19:23.140
if you put a yellow
pencil in glass,

01:19:23.140 --> 01:19:24.310
the pencil remains yellow.

01:19:24.310 --> 01:19:27.180
It does not turn blue, right?

01:19:27.180 --> 01:19:30.650
So what is a possible-- does
anybody know the explanation?

01:19:30.650 --> 01:19:32.315
Yeah.

01:19:32.315 --> 01:19:33.940
AUDIENCE: The frequency
stays the same.

01:19:33.940 --> 01:19:36.835
So if you see the
frequency as it comes out,

01:19:36.835 --> 01:19:39.210
it's just going to be affecting
pretty much [INAUDIBLE]..

01:19:39.210 --> 01:19:40.627
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
That's right.

01:19:42.850 --> 01:19:45.940
So very correctly, he said
that the frequency of the light

01:19:45.940 --> 01:19:47.350
remains the same.

01:19:47.350 --> 01:19:50.320
Anybody want to guess why
the frequency of the light

01:19:50.320 --> 01:19:55.600
might remain the same but
the wavelength can change?

01:20:03.140 --> 01:20:04.307
AUDIENCE: The speed changes.

01:20:04.307 --> 01:20:05.723
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
That's right.

01:20:05.723 --> 01:20:06.588
The speed, yes.

01:20:10.046 --> 01:20:10.750
That's right.

01:20:10.750 --> 01:20:12.840
So both of you are right.

01:20:12.840 --> 01:20:15.810
So first of all, they can
change simultaneously,

01:20:15.810 --> 01:20:19.440
the wavelength and the speed,
because of this equation.

01:20:19.440 --> 01:20:21.950
We said that the
speed of light--

01:20:21.950 --> 01:20:26.720
I mean the speed of light
in vacuum, or in general--

01:20:26.720 --> 01:20:31.410
well, in vacuum, it is
related to the frequency

01:20:31.410 --> 01:20:33.900
of the wavelength by
this equation over here.

01:20:33.900 --> 01:20:37.860
Well, you can then divide the
two sides of the equation by n,

01:20:37.860 --> 01:20:39.787
and the question
remains the same.

01:20:39.787 --> 01:20:40.995
But that's not very physical.

01:20:40.995 --> 01:20:42.352
I did a mathematical trick.

01:20:42.352 --> 01:20:43.560
What the hell does that mean?

01:20:43.560 --> 01:20:45.020
I divided both sides by n.

01:20:48.212 --> 01:20:50.420
That doesn't have to be
correct, and this is, indeed,

01:20:50.420 --> 01:20:54.910
the dispersion relation in
a dielectrical material.

01:20:54.910 --> 01:20:57.820
But you don't really know,
which one should you divide?

01:20:57.820 --> 01:20:59.770
Should you divide
the wavelength by n,

01:20:59.770 --> 01:21:02.200
or should you divide
the frequency by n?

01:21:02.200 --> 01:21:04.840
Or maybe divide both
by square root n?

01:21:04.840 --> 01:21:06.530
All of these are possibilities.

01:21:06.530 --> 01:21:10.660
So the physical argument
that allows you to decide

01:21:10.660 --> 01:21:12.410
whether to divide is what--

01:21:12.410 --> 01:21:13.600
I'm sorry, your name?

01:21:13.600 --> 01:21:14.020
AUDIENCE: Uh, Liz.

01:21:14.020 --> 01:21:14.950
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
What Alice--

01:21:14.950 --> 01:21:15.648
Alice, right?

01:21:15.648 --> 01:21:16.440
AUDIENCE: Just Liz.

01:21:16.440 --> 01:21:17.940
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Liz, I'm sorry.

01:21:17.940 --> 01:21:21.740
So the physical argument
is what Liz just said,

01:21:21.740 --> 01:21:26.950
which is that the energy of
the photon cannot change.

01:21:26.950 --> 01:21:29.650
Because the photon-- well,
I haven't said it yet,

01:21:29.650 --> 01:21:34.110
but the photon is a fundamental
quantum mechanical particle.

01:21:34.110 --> 01:21:35.920
It cannot be divided--

01:21:35.920 --> 01:21:39.310
well, it can be divided
in some special cases.

01:21:39.310 --> 01:21:43.120
But in the approximation
that we deal with here,

01:21:43.120 --> 01:21:45.860
the photon must
maintain its energy.

01:21:45.860 --> 01:21:47.860
So therefore, the
frequency of the photon

01:21:47.860 --> 01:21:49.640
must remain the same.

01:21:49.640 --> 01:21:53.890
New, the temporal
frequency is conserved.

01:21:53.890 --> 01:21:56.890
So if the wavelength changes
because light entered

01:21:56.890 --> 01:21:59.290
into matter, then
the velocity must

01:21:59.290 --> 01:22:04.278
change to compensate in the
dispersion relationship.

01:22:04.278 --> 01:22:08.590
OK, in our context
here, the only thing

01:22:08.590 --> 01:22:13.617
that can happen to the
photon is it can disappear.

01:22:13.617 --> 01:22:14.950
And it doesn't really disappear.

01:22:14.950 --> 01:22:16.840
It gets converted
to heat, right?

01:22:16.840 --> 01:22:19.270
So when the light
hits the material,

01:22:19.270 --> 01:22:22.980
it actually heats the
material in discrete quanta.

01:22:22.980 --> 01:22:27.300
Some of the photons that
come from the light source,

01:22:27.300 --> 01:22:31.620
discrete quantities
that are equal to--

01:22:31.620 --> 01:22:33.810
you cannot see it over
there because I erased it.

01:22:33.810 --> 01:22:36.210
But discrete quantities
of approximately 10

01:22:36.210 --> 01:22:40.560
to the minus 19 joules,
one of them at a time

01:22:40.560 --> 01:22:43.800
can be converted to heat
and heat the material.

01:22:43.800 --> 01:22:48.330
But you cannot get 60% of the
photon energy to go to heat

01:22:48.330 --> 01:22:49.200
the material.

01:22:49.200 --> 01:22:51.330
That's not the correct
way to think about it.

01:22:51.330 --> 01:22:54.540
If 60% of the energy goes
into heating the material,

01:22:54.540 --> 01:22:57.840
it means that 60% of
individual photons

01:22:57.840 --> 01:23:02.580
died and gave up their energy to
the molecules of the material.

01:23:02.580 --> 01:23:05.690
If you have a single photon
arriving into a material,

01:23:05.690 --> 01:23:08.690
it will either survive
and go through impact,

01:23:08.690 --> 01:23:10.820
or it will die and
be converted to heat.

01:23:10.820 --> 01:23:13.980
You cannot have 60% of an
individual photon heating

01:23:13.980 --> 01:23:15.280
the material.

01:23:15.280 --> 01:23:17.220
OK, so because of this
line of reasoning,

01:23:17.220 --> 01:23:18.845
that really requires
quantum mechanics.

01:23:18.845 --> 01:23:22.160
So I cannot really justify
it very well without spending

01:23:22.160 --> 01:23:23.710
a semester of quantum mechanics.

01:23:23.710 --> 01:23:25.640
But because of this
line of reasoning,

01:23:25.640 --> 01:23:28.460
the energy of the
photon is invalid.

01:23:28.460 --> 01:23:31.490
Therefore, nu is invariant.

01:23:31.490 --> 01:23:34.540
So believe it or not, I have
watched someone at a conference

01:23:34.540 --> 01:23:37.473
stand up and say, well, doesn't
the light really become green?

01:23:37.473 --> 01:23:38.890
And that was an
optics conference,

01:23:38.890 --> 01:23:40.550
so it was very embarrassing.

01:23:40.550 --> 01:23:42.850
But it's very
useful to remember.

01:23:42.850 --> 01:23:50.120
No, light does not become
green when it enters glass.

01:23:50.120 --> 01:23:52.875
And in any case, your
eyes respond to the energy

01:23:52.875 --> 01:23:53.750
of the photon, right?

01:23:53.750 --> 01:23:57.950
Because-- well, I haven't said
how your eyes perceive color

01:23:57.950 --> 01:23:59.480
yet, but they respond
to the energy.

01:23:59.480 --> 01:24:01.605
So you still perceive it
as red, because the energy

01:24:01.605 --> 01:24:06.570
of the photon is still red.

01:24:06.570 --> 01:24:11.030
OK, so having said
that now, having

01:24:11.030 --> 01:24:13.910
said that the
index of refraction

01:24:13.910 --> 01:24:17.060
is a property of the material,
I can conceive of materials

01:24:17.060 --> 01:24:21.207
where the index of refraction
is a function of position.

01:24:21.207 --> 01:24:22.290
And if that was the case--

01:24:26.157 --> 01:24:27.615
the bad thing about
any measures is

01:24:27.615 --> 01:24:29.720
you have to wait
for them to finish.

01:24:29.720 --> 01:24:31.950
OK, so you can
conceive materials

01:24:31.950 --> 01:24:34.140
where the index of
refraction is variable.

01:24:34.140 --> 01:24:36.780
So the example I gave
before is the air, where,

01:24:36.780 --> 01:24:40.480
because of temperature,
pressure, and so on,

01:24:40.480 --> 01:24:41.830
the index changes.

01:24:41.830 --> 01:24:43.540
So if the index is
functional position,

01:24:43.540 --> 01:24:46.805
you can define a quantity that
is called the optical path

01:24:46.805 --> 01:24:47.305
length.

01:24:47.305 --> 01:24:50.430
So if you follow the
trajectory of the ray--

01:24:50.430 --> 01:24:53.580
so here is the ray, and
that is its trajectory--

01:24:53.580 --> 01:24:59.650
you can integrate the
index of refraction

01:24:59.650 --> 01:25:03.190
in small, individual segments
as the light propagates

01:25:03.190 --> 01:25:06.450
along the ray.

01:25:06.450 --> 01:25:09.210
So the basic
principle that I would

01:25:09.210 --> 01:25:12.810
like you to carry with you
when you leave this class today

01:25:12.810 --> 01:25:16.140
is that the basic
law that covers

01:25:16.140 --> 01:25:20.780
light propagation in
the ray description

01:25:20.780 --> 01:25:22.950
is that this quantity,
the optical path,

01:25:22.950 --> 01:25:23.850
must be preserved--

01:25:23.850 --> 01:25:25.963
I'm sorry, it must be minimized.

01:25:25.963 --> 01:25:27.380
Of course, it has
to be preserved.

01:25:27.380 --> 01:25:29.475
It also has to be minimized.

01:25:29.475 --> 01:25:31.350
So if you have different
paths-- for example,

01:25:31.350 --> 01:25:35.480
if you compare the path gamma
and the path gamma prime--

01:25:35.480 --> 01:25:40.510
the light will take the path
where this quantity is minimal,

01:25:40.510 --> 01:25:41.415
OK?

01:25:41.415 --> 01:25:43.040
Now, that sounds very
abstract, I know,

01:25:43.040 --> 01:25:45.650
but I will make it more
specific with examples.

01:25:45.650 --> 01:25:47.990
For those of you who are
mechanical engineers-- or, more

01:25:47.990 --> 01:25:50.030
likely, applied
mechanicians-- this

01:25:50.030 --> 01:25:51.710
is reminiscent of
another principle

01:25:51.710 --> 01:25:55.010
that you may have learned in
your Lagrangian mechanics.

01:25:55.010 --> 01:25:58.790
You can make the same,
the exact same arguments

01:25:58.790 --> 01:26:02.510
about particles moving
in a gravitational field.

01:26:02.510 --> 01:26:04.670
Particles moving in--
that's the reason

01:26:04.670 --> 01:26:07.660
why stars rotate
around the sun, why

01:26:07.660 --> 01:26:09.110
they have elliptical
trajectories,

01:26:09.110 --> 01:26:11.140
and so on, and so forth--
is because they also

01:26:11.140 --> 01:26:16.200
obey a minimum path principle.

01:26:16.200 --> 01:26:21.320
And well, let's see
it in action here.

01:26:21.320 --> 01:26:23.590
So we apply this
principle-- we'll

01:26:23.590 --> 01:26:25.600
apply it in several
occasions during the class,

01:26:25.600 --> 01:26:29.290
but today, I would like
to apply to discover

01:26:29.290 --> 01:26:31.570
what happens to
light when it arrives

01:26:31.570 --> 01:26:34.490
at an interface
between two dialectics.

01:26:34.490 --> 01:26:38.058
So on the left, you have
one dielectric-- say air--

01:26:38.058 --> 01:26:39.850
and on the right-hand
side of an interface,

01:26:39.850 --> 01:26:42.705
you have another
dielectric-- say glass.

01:26:42.705 --> 01:26:44.080
So what will happen
to the light?

01:26:44.080 --> 01:26:46.180
Well, two things will happen.

01:26:46.180 --> 01:26:48.250
Some fraction of the
light energy-- that is,

01:26:48.250 --> 01:26:52.060
some fraction of
individual photons--

01:26:52.060 --> 01:26:54.080
will be reflected.

01:26:54.080 --> 01:26:59.440
And some other fraction of the
light will enter the interface,

01:26:59.440 --> 01:27:02.080
but it might enter
at an angle that

01:27:02.080 --> 01:27:04.240
is different than
the angle of arrival.

01:27:07.710 --> 01:27:12.120
That portion of light that
goes in, we call it refracted.

01:27:12.120 --> 01:27:14.370
So this is the refracted
portion of the light.

01:27:14.370 --> 01:27:16.710
It's a little bit confusing,
because the two terms

01:27:16.710 --> 01:27:19.020
are the same except
for two letters.

01:27:19.020 --> 01:27:21.690
So I hope you can sort of
recapture the difference.

01:27:21.690 --> 01:27:26.010
One is reflected, and
the other is refracted.

01:27:26.010 --> 01:27:28.750
So the question is, what is
the direction that these rays

01:27:28.750 --> 01:27:31.040
propagate at the interface?

01:27:31.040 --> 01:27:34.810
So we will invoke the minimal
path principle for that.

01:27:34.810 --> 01:27:36.750
So consider, first, reflection.

01:27:36.750 --> 01:27:38.220
And what I'm about
to say applies

01:27:38.220 --> 01:27:42.600
to the electric interface just
as well as a mirror, a metal

01:27:42.600 --> 01:27:45.080
or metallic mirror.

01:27:45.080 --> 01:27:46.910
So the minimum
path principle says

01:27:46.910 --> 01:27:49.850
that the light must be
reflected symmetrically.

01:27:49.850 --> 01:27:54.200
So the reflected ray
makes the same angle

01:27:54.200 --> 01:27:57.078
with the normal as the
incident ray, because that's

01:27:57.078 --> 01:27:58.120
the minimum path, really.

01:27:58.120 --> 01:28:04.140
If you force the light to
go to a different path--

01:28:04.140 --> 01:28:06.308
for example, this way--

01:28:06.308 --> 01:28:08.850
then you can see very easily,
it is a very simple calculation

01:28:08.850 --> 01:28:16.192
to show that P, O, tilde p-prime
is longer than P, O, P, OK?

01:28:16.192 --> 01:28:18.150
I will let you think
about that on your selves.

01:28:18.150 --> 01:28:21.390
You can very easily convince
yourselves that this is true.

01:28:21.390 --> 01:28:25.170
And therefore, the light must
follow the symmetric path.

01:28:25.170 --> 01:28:26.850
So this is rule number one.

01:28:26.850 --> 01:28:29.660
Let me skip the next slide.

01:28:29.660 --> 01:28:32.980
I'll skip a little bit, and then
I'll come back to this later.

01:28:32.980 --> 01:28:35.010
But I want to first
say something else.

01:28:44.690 --> 01:28:47.120
OK.

01:28:47.120 --> 01:28:49.150
When we think about the law of--

01:28:49.150 --> 01:28:52.070
let's say we think about
the refracted light.

01:28:52.070 --> 01:28:54.220
The [INAUDIBLE] is the medium.

01:28:54.220 --> 01:28:56.680
OK, so the first thing
we need to do in order

01:28:56.680 --> 01:28:59.938
to complete this calculation
is to define two points

01:28:59.938 --> 01:29:00.480
from the ray.

01:29:00.480 --> 01:29:03.550
So let's say you have
point p on the incident ray

01:29:03.550 --> 01:29:06.460
and then point p-prime
on the refracted ray.

01:29:09.250 --> 01:29:12.560
So let's compute this
quantity of the optical path.

01:29:12.560 --> 01:29:15.910
So the optical part
equals the index

01:29:15.910 --> 01:29:18.460
of refraction on
the leg on the left,

01:29:18.460 --> 01:29:21.790
times the length
of the day from p

01:29:21.790 --> 01:29:25.525
to the interface, and then
the index of refraction

01:29:25.525 --> 01:29:28.270
in n prime on the
right-hand side,

01:29:28.270 --> 01:29:32.430
times the length of the ray
from the interface to p prime.

01:29:32.430 --> 01:29:35.280
So this, I will repeat
what I have on the slide.

01:29:35.280 --> 01:29:37.072
I will repeat it
on the blackboard.

01:29:41.010 --> 01:29:45.250
So you have n times
the hypotenuse.

01:29:45.250 --> 01:29:47.805
So my notation here is
x for this distance,

01:29:47.805 --> 01:29:49.980
z for this distance.

01:29:49.980 --> 01:29:58.350
So that's the
hypotenuse plus n prime,

01:29:58.350 --> 01:30:01.600
times the other hypotenuse.

01:30:01.600 --> 01:30:05.340
So this other hypotenuse, if
I call h the vertical distance

01:30:05.340 --> 01:30:08.160
between the two
points, simple geometry

01:30:08.160 --> 01:30:10.300
solves that this
other hypotenuse

01:30:10.300 --> 01:30:11.660
is something like that.

01:30:19.610 --> 01:30:27.570
OK, so the question here--

01:30:27.570 --> 01:30:28.860
how do I pose the question?

01:30:28.860 --> 01:30:29.960
What is the unknown here?

01:30:38.700 --> 01:30:42.930
What have I left unspecified?

01:30:42.930 --> 01:30:45.170
Let me start with what I
have already specified.

01:30:45.170 --> 01:30:47.810
I specified theta, the
angle of incidence.

01:30:47.810 --> 01:30:51.060
I specified the two
points, p and p prime.

01:30:51.060 --> 01:30:55.225
And I specified the
vertical distance h.

01:30:55.225 --> 01:30:56.850
And also, I should
say that the z prime

01:30:56.850 --> 01:31:01.750
is also specified, because z and
z prime are specified because,

01:31:01.750 --> 01:31:04.560
OK, I have specified the
coordinates of p and p prime.

01:31:04.560 --> 01:31:05.130
What is left?

01:31:08.080 --> 01:31:14.178
theta prime, or another quantity
that is also left unspecified?

01:31:18.760 --> 01:31:21.150
x and x prime, right?

01:31:21.150 --> 01:31:23.120
Because the ray
might go like this.

01:31:27.730 --> 01:31:30.910
All we know is that
the line starts at p

01:31:30.910 --> 01:31:32.740
and ends at p prime.

01:31:32.740 --> 01:31:33.880
It can go like this.

01:31:33.880 --> 01:31:35.200
It can go like this.

01:31:35.200 --> 01:31:36.420
It can go like this.

01:31:36.420 --> 01:31:37.990
It can go like this, right?

01:31:37.990 --> 01:31:39.830
Which is the case?

01:31:39.830 --> 01:31:41.860
OK, so therefore,
each one of those

01:31:41.860 --> 01:31:43.900
has a different value of x.

01:31:43.900 --> 01:31:46.850
So how do we find x?

01:31:46.850 --> 01:31:52.520
Well, Fermat says that light
must minimize this quantity.

01:31:52.520 --> 01:31:55.120
The quantity that I
wrote on the blackboard

01:31:55.120 --> 01:31:59.540
and on the slide, Fermat says
that it has to be minimized.

01:31:59.540 --> 01:32:03.320
And OPL, by the way, stands
for Optical Path Length.

01:32:03.320 --> 01:32:05.070
So to minimize it,
I have to compute

01:32:05.070 --> 01:32:10.400
the derivative of this quantity
with respect to my unknown.

01:32:10.400 --> 01:32:13.813
I manage to have only one
unknown of this quantity.

01:32:13.813 --> 01:32:15.980
To find this unknown, I'd
better take the derivative

01:32:15.980 --> 01:32:17.190
and set it to 0.

01:32:17.190 --> 01:32:22.510
So if I take the derivative,
I will get n times--

01:32:22.510 --> 01:32:23.590
what is the derivative?

01:32:23.590 --> 01:32:24.090
Someone?

01:32:29.378 --> 01:32:31.170
I guess I've had more
coffee than everyone,

01:32:31.170 --> 01:32:32.825
so I can still do
the derivative.

01:32:32.825 --> 01:32:35.960
So it is nx divided
by the square root,

01:32:35.960 --> 01:32:42.600
minus n prime h minus x, divided
by the other square root, OK?

01:32:45.590 --> 01:32:47.420
OK, give me, now, a
simple observation that

01:32:47.420 --> 01:32:48.670
solves the problem right away.

01:32:57.850 --> 01:32:58.880
That's right.

01:32:58.880 --> 01:33:07.240
This quantity, x
over the hypotenuse,

01:33:07.240 --> 01:33:08.480
is the sign of this angle.

01:33:08.480 --> 01:33:12.110
This angle is the same
as this angle, right?

01:33:12.110 --> 01:33:15.018
Therefore, this
quantity is its sine.

01:33:15.018 --> 01:33:16.310
And the same for the other one.

01:33:16.310 --> 01:33:23.000
The other quantity over here
is the sine of theta prime.

01:33:23.000 --> 01:33:27.770
So if you substitute these
quantities into the derivation,

01:33:27.770 --> 01:33:32.490
then you find this
relationship over here.

01:33:32.490 --> 01:33:38.770
n times sine theta must equal
n prime times sine theta prime.

01:33:38.770 --> 01:33:42.600
And this is the law of
refraction, also known

01:33:42.600 --> 01:33:43.380
as Snell's Law.

01:33:50.320 --> 01:33:53.560
So officially, I think,
we're out of time.

01:33:53.560 --> 01:33:56.940
But I can take a
couple of very few--

01:33:56.940 --> 01:33:59.720
I should say very
quick questions,

01:33:59.720 --> 01:34:02.148
about that or about
anything else.

01:34:02.148 --> 01:34:04.320
Yes?

01:34:04.320 --> 01:34:09.880
AUDIENCE: So how is it that
you can assume p and p prime,

01:34:09.880 --> 01:34:11.990
without knowing
these other things?

01:34:11.990 --> 01:34:13.365
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
OK, so I was

01:34:13.365 --> 01:34:15.443
hoping that you would ask that.

01:34:15.443 --> 01:34:16.610
That's a very good question.

01:34:16.610 --> 01:34:19.080
So the way this
problem is solved

01:34:19.080 --> 01:34:26.310
is as follows I take for granted
that there is a light ray that

01:34:26.310 --> 01:34:28.610
goes between p and p prime.

01:34:28.610 --> 01:34:30.110
The reason I can
take it for granted

01:34:30.110 --> 01:34:32.340
is another very basic
principle that says

01:34:32.340 --> 01:34:35.040
that if I have a light source--

01:34:35.040 --> 01:34:40.430
say it's p-- then
light propagates

01:34:40.430 --> 01:34:43.460
in spherical bundles.

01:34:43.460 --> 01:34:52.130
So I will actually have many,
many rays coming from p.

01:34:52.130 --> 01:34:57.090
And if I have another point,
any point out here, p prime,

01:34:57.090 --> 01:35:03.730
I will also have many,
many rays arriving here

01:35:03.730 --> 01:35:05.720
from the left-hand side.

01:35:05.720 --> 01:35:09.420
One of these rays
has come from p.

01:35:09.420 --> 01:35:14.280
So the question is, how
can you connect these rays?

01:35:14.280 --> 01:35:18.450
Well, the principle that
allows you to connect them

01:35:18.450 --> 01:35:21.180
is the minimum path principle.

01:35:21.180 --> 01:35:22.860
The problem can
become impossible.

01:35:22.860 --> 01:35:25.680
I will show you examples
later where, in fact, you

01:35:25.680 --> 01:35:29.723
might have a case where
no rays reach p prime.

01:35:29.723 --> 01:35:30.640
You can see that here.

01:35:30.640 --> 01:35:32.970
If I play with the numbers
and make one of these--

01:35:32.970 --> 01:35:35.940
if I play with the numbers
so that one of the sines

01:35:35.940 --> 01:35:39.320
becomes bigger than 1, then
the problem becomes impossible,

01:35:39.320 --> 01:35:39.820
right?

01:35:39.820 --> 01:35:42.210
So what it means is that
light never makes it there.

01:35:45.760 --> 01:35:48.940
So this way of thinking
is very typical

01:35:48.940 --> 01:35:53.680
when we deal with minimization
principles like Fermat

01:35:53.680 --> 01:35:56.800
and Lagrangian
principles in mechanics.

01:35:56.800 --> 01:35:59.830
We assume that our
particle, or our system,

01:35:59.830 --> 01:36:03.270
or whatever has followed
a trajectory that

01:36:03.270 --> 01:36:06.880
connects an initial point in
the space with the final point

01:36:06.880 --> 01:36:08.100
in the space.

01:36:08.100 --> 01:36:10.480
And then we try to find a
trajectory that minimizes

01:36:10.480 --> 01:36:13.450
the part between the two points,
whether it is optical path

01:36:13.450 --> 01:36:17.800
length, or Lagrangian
in mechanics,

01:36:17.800 --> 01:36:20.380
or a lot of other
different contexts

01:36:20.380 --> 01:36:22.660
where the same thinking applied.

01:36:29.760 --> 01:36:31.057
Any other questions?

